1
00:00:06,000 --> 00:00:12,074


2
00:01:29,925 --> 00:01:33,121
All right. 2:30 tomorrow.
Thank you. Goodbye.

3
00:01:34,308 --> 00:01:35,737
Thanks, Sergeant.

4
00:01:35,812 --> 00:01:38,147
Report of horse rations,
Thirtieth Hussars.

5
00:01:38,213 --> 00:01:39,423
Regimental
and general files.

6
00:01:39,492 --> 00:01:42,209
Now, each of these buttons represents troops.
Do you understand?

7
00:01:42,276 --> 00:01:43,454
Yes, sir.
Good.

8
00:01:44,004 --> 00:01:46,557
The buttons are thickest up near
the Northwest Frontier.

9
00:01:46,628 --> 00:01:47,888
Oh, yes, always.

10
00:01:47,948 --> 00:01:50,315
We have 300 million
people to protect.

11
00:01:51,020 --> 00:01:52,749
And most of the danger
is there.

12
00:01:52,817 --> 00:01:55,184
It's so romantic
to a greenhorn like me.

13
00:01:55,249 --> 00:01:56,493
Kipling and all that,
you know.

14
00:01:56,561 --> 00:01:57,838
Romantic?

15
00:01:58,162 --> 00:01:59,853
Well, at first, yes.

16
00:02:01,265 --> 00:02:03,240
A- another button
to move.

17
00:02:03,889 --> 00:02:05,929
41st Bengal Lancers.

18
00:02:07,762 --> 00:02:09,769
Here, near the pass.

19
00:02:09,841 --> 00:02:11,751
The pass?
Does that mean-

20
00:02:11,817 --> 00:02:13,589
It means nothing
but maneuvers.

21
00:02:13,656 --> 00:02:16,242
As CoI. Stone says
in his report here.

22
00:02:24,319 --> 00:02:25,748
You hear that firing,
Hamilton?

23
00:02:25,823 --> 00:02:27,546
Typical sniping fire, sir.

24
00:02:27,614 --> 00:02:29,949
Yes, and Afridi muskets
every one of them.

25
00:02:30,015 --> 00:02:32,055
Not a shot
from our detachment.

26
00:02:32,126 --> 00:02:34,582
Good. Hendrickson's
a good soldier.

27
00:02:35,006 --> 00:02:36,061
Rough on him,

28
00:02:36,133 --> 00:02:38,751
having those Afridi swine
popping away at his men

29
00:02:38,821 --> 00:02:40,512
and not able
to return fire.

30
00:02:40,581 --> 00:02:42,954
Well, he'll get a citation
if this plan works.

31
00:02:43,019 --> 00:02:46,281
Plan's good enough, sir,
if it were anybody but Mohammed Khan.

32
00:02:46,795 --> 00:02:48,169
He's a clever dog.

33
00:02:48,236 --> 00:02:51,018
Yes, of course he is.
I ought to know.

34
00:02:51,532 --> 00:02:53,899
But he's nibbling
at our bait this time.

35
00:02:53,963 --> 00:02:55,621
And if we can once
draw him down

36
00:02:55,691 --> 00:02:58,026
out of those hills
far enough, out into the open

37
00:02:58,092 --> 00:02:59,976
so that we can
cut off his retreat,

38
00:03:00,050 --> 00:03:01,992
we've got him red-handed!

39
00:03:03,827 --> 00:03:05,932
And that's what
I've been waiting for,

40
00:03:06,066 --> 00:03:08,461
for 15 years, Hamilton.

41
00:03:39,301 --> 00:03:41,756
Afridi swine. When do we
go into action, Hendrickson?

42
00:03:41,829 --> 00:03:43,804
On no account return fire.
CoI. Stone's orders.

43
00:03:43,878 --> 00:03:44,860
ColoneI's orders.

44
00:03:51,085 --> 00:03:52,394
Narain Singh.

45
00:03:53,228 --> 00:03:54,438
Now can we start something?

46
00:03:54,508 --> 00:03:55,556
ColoneI's orders,
McGregor.

47
00:03:55,629 --> 00:03:57,483
But the old fool
couldn't have foreseen this.

48
00:03:57,555 --> 00:03:59,081
I'd like to have you
with me in a war,

49
00:03:59,154 --> 00:04:00,681
but for peace time,
you're a bit too-

50
00:04:15,514 --> 00:04:16,724
Too...

51
00:04:17,434 --> 00:04:18,960
Too impulsive.

52
00:04:30,975 --> 00:04:31,990
Machine guns!

53
00:04:52,076 --> 00:04:53,735
Forward!

54
00:05:36,800 --> 00:05:37,886
Most unfortunate,

55
00:05:37,958 --> 00:05:39,584
the command
devolved upon you.

56
00:05:39,655 --> 00:05:41,443
Of course you didn't
know my orders.

57
00:05:41,734 --> 00:05:43,360
I did know them, sir.

58
00:05:43,431 --> 00:05:45,089
Why didn't
you obey them?

59
00:05:53,485 --> 00:05:55,590
You call yourself
a soldier?

60
00:05:57,997 --> 00:05:59,372
That's all.

61
00:06:05,044 --> 00:06:06,986
The Colonel knows India,
McGregor. You don't.

62
00:06:07,060 --> 00:06:08,008
You're right, I don't.

63
00:06:08,083 --> 00:06:09,774
I'm just a fooI
Scotch-Canadian.

64
00:06:09,844 --> 00:06:11,728
Came into your outfit
to get action.

65
00:06:11,802 --> 00:06:13,427
He's got a ramrod
for a backbone.

66
00:06:13,498 --> 00:06:16,281
He's a terror for drilling,
but when it comes to the real thing-

67
00:06:16,346 --> 00:06:18,353
McGregor,
the Colonel has the right

68
00:06:18,426 --> 00:06:20,979
to act as he thinks best
and say what he pleases.

69
00:06:45,576 --> 00:06:47,102
Mount!

70
00:07:05,588 --> 00:07:07,312
One more thing, sir.

71
00:07:08,212 --> 00:07:10,830
Two replacements come in
today from Delhi.

72
00:07:11,540 --> 00:07:12,555
Paperwork.

73
00:07:14,388 --> 00:07:16,909
When we came into
the regiment as boys,

74
00:07:16,981 --> 00:07:19,637
we didn't know that this
was 9l10ths of soldiering.

75
00:07:19,706 --> 00:07:20,655
No.

76
00:07:21,179 --> 00:07:23,804
We thought and acted
rather like McGregor.

77
00:07:23,873 --> 00:07:24,986
Mmm.

78
00:07:25,825 --> 00:07:27,418
What about
these two replacements?

79
00:07:27,489 --> 00:07:28,863
What are they sending
to us now?

80
00:07:28,929 --> 00:07:30,839
From the Blues:
Lt. Forsythe.

81
00:07:30,914 --> 00:07:33,335
The Blues, eh? Well, that's
a fashionable regiment.

82
00:07:33,409 --> 00:07:35,929
All spit and polish.
Who's the other one?

83
00:07:36,001 --> 00:07:38,303
From Sandhurst:
Lt. Stone.

84
00:07:38,785 --> 00:07:39,713
What?

85
00:07:39,777 --> 00:07:41,271
From Sandhurst?

86
00:07:41,345 --> 00:07:43,555
What, they're sending me
a young cub,

87
00:07:43,623 --> 00:07:46,657
not dry behind
the ears yet? Unseasoned?

88
00:07:46,728 --> 00:07:48,808
Straight from,
fr-from military college

89
00:07:48,879 --> 00:07:50,056
to the Frontier?

90
00:07:50,574 --> 00:07:52,068
Oh, bless me.

91
00:07:52,302 --> 00:07:54,277
Hmm, what'd you say
his name was?

92
00:07:54,350 --> 00:07:56,172
Donald Stone, sir.
Hmm.

93
00:08:00,686 --> 00:08:02,213
And who asked you
to interfere

94
00:08:02,286 --> 00:08:03,431
in my personal affairs?

95
00:08:03,502 --> 00:08:05,193
Will you forget
that you're my coloneI

96
00:08:05,262 --> 00:08:06,472
for a moment, sir?

97
00:08:08,116 --> 00:08:09,196
Yes.

98
00:08:13,019 --> 00:08:14,513
Look here, Tom.

99
00:08:14,587 --> 00:08:17,075
In about two years,
you'll be retired.

100
00:08:18,107 --> 00:08:19,569
So you sent for my son

101
00:08:19,643 --> 00:08:21,683
because you feel sorry
for me, is that it?

102
00:08:21,756 --> 00:08:22,966
Not at all.

103
00:08:23,035 --> 00:08:25,555
The idea was to keep
the name of Stone

104
00:08:25,627 --> 00:08:27,831
in the 41st
after you're gone.

105
00:08:28,283 --> 00:08:31,218
There's no room for
sentimentality in the army.

106
00:08:33,857 --> 00:08:36,734
Hardly fair to ship him home
without a triaI.

107
00:08:39,944 --> 00:08:42,180
Still, he'll measure up
to my standards,

108
00:08:42,249 --> 00:08:43,459
or out he goes.

109
00:08:43,528 --> 00:08:44,476
Of course.

110
00:08:44,552 --> 00:08:46,821
And at the first sign
of favoritism,

111
00:08:46,920 --> 00:08:48,993
from you or anyone else,

112
00:08:49,736 --> 00:08:51,230
there'll be trouble.

113
00:08:51,400 --> 00:08:53,789
And that's an order,
Maj. Hamilton.

114
00:09:00,725 --> 00:09:02,415
Just as you said,
Major.

115
00:09:02,485 --> 00:09:03,980
It's the ColoneI's
privilege

116
00:09:04,053 --> 00:09:05,363
to do
and say what he likes.

117
00:09:06,965 --> 00:09:09,583
McGregor, you'll meet
the two replacement officers this morning.

118
00:09:09,653 --> 00:09:11,115
Lts. Forsythe and Stone.

119
00:09:11,189 --> 00:09:12,814
Yes, sir. S-Stone?

120
00:09:13,717 --> 00:09:14,731
His son.

121
00:09:15,061 --> 00:09:16,239
His what?

122
00:09:16,309 --> 00:09:17,716
I said, his son.

123
00:09:20,757 --> 00:09:24,350
I can't imagine old Ramrod
ever having been that human.

124
00:09:26,530 --> 00:09:28,602
The train arrives at 10:30,
Mr. McGregor.

125
00:09:28,674 --> 00:09:29,983
Yes, sir.

126
00:09:37,506 --> 00:09:40,092
Madam, you'll marry me
Tuesday the 29th.

127
00:09:40,162 --> 00:09:42,464
Be at the church at 10:00.
That's an order.

128
00:09:42,530 --> 00:09:46,043
Furthermore,
you're improperly dressed.

129
00:09:47,631 --> 00:09:48,743
Ha, Ha.

130
00:09:51,503 --> 00:09:53,608
Did you want
to speak to me, McGregor?

131
00:09:53,679 --> 00:09:54,956
No, sir.

132
00:10:15,901 --> 00:10:17,144
I hope he's a nice follow.

133
00:10:17,212 --> 00:10:18,805
He won't be. Ramrod.

134
00:10:18,876 --> 00:10:20,087
I beg your pardon?

135
00:10:20,156 --> 00:10:22,577
One Stone isn't enough.
We have to have two.

136
00:10:26,716 --> 00:10:29,366
There he is,
the younger Ramrod himself.

137
00:10:29,820 --> 00:10:32,089
Everything was all right?
Thank you, sir.

138
00:10:32,956 --> 00:10:35,997
Couldn't be anybody else.
Just as sure of himself as...

139
00:10:36,803 --> 00:10:38,434
Look at the way
they jump around for him.

140
00:10:38,505 --> 00:10:41,058
Look at his luggage,
everything just so-so.

141
00:10:41,257 --> 00:10:44,159
Well, come on,
let's get it over with.

142
00:10:44,233 --> 00:10:45,989
No, I've got
a little business.

143
00:10:46,057 --> 00:10:48,064
You get
your precious replacements.

144
00:10:55,913 --> 00:10:58,149
I'm McGregor, Lancers,
sent to meet you.

145
00:10:58,217 --> 00:11:00,713
Oh, sort of
reception committee, eh?

146
00:11:01,424 --> 00:11:03,438
It's nice to know
I was expected.

147
00:11:03,894 --> 00:11:06,709
The regiment's been
practically breathless for a week.

148
00:11:06,774 --> 00:11:07,919
Oh?

149
00:11:07,990 --> 00:11:09,746
Traveling light, huh?

150
00:11:13,878 --> 00:11:17,042
Well, you see, I did expect
to stay a little while.

151
00:11:17,110 --> 00:11:18,997
That is if you don't
mind too much.

152
00:11:19,062 --> 00:11:20,950
It's all right
with me.

153
00:11:22,836 --> 00:11:23,893
Goodbye.

154
00:11:23,965 --> 00:11:25,874
And thank you very much
for being so kind.

155
00:11:25,949 --> 00:11:26,898
Not at all.

156
00:11:26,973 --> 00:11:28,987
Your luggage and everything
all taken care of?

157
00:11:29,059 --> 00:11:30,269
Everything, thank you.

158
00:11:30,339 --> 00:11:31,833
May I present Mr. McGregor,
Miss Leys?

159
00:11:31,907 --> 00:11:33,500
Very happy.
How do you do?

160
00:11:33,571 --> 00:11:34,465
Goodbye.

161
00:11:34,531 --> 00:11:35,840
Goodbye.
Goodbye.

162
00:11:38,627 --> 00:11:39,739
Who's she?

163
00:11:39,811 --> 00:11:42,593
I met her on the train,
if you don't mind.

164
00:11:43,395 --> 00:11:45,883
Bad business talking
to strange people out here.

165
00:11:45,955 --> 00:11:47,056
You know, this is India.

166
00:11:47,126 --> 00:11:48,969
You don't know who they are,
and you might-

167
00:11:49,034 --> 00:11:51,936
Oh, I see.
BeautifuI spy meets the young Lancer officer,

168
00:11:52,010 --> 00:11:55,050
makes him give away
important military secrets.

169
00:11:55,120 --> 00:11:57,007
The Empire goes smash.

170
00:11:57,264 --> 00:11:59,981
Melodrama, my dear McGregor,
melodrama.

171
00:12:00,976 --> 00:12:03,529
It might not be as funny
as it sounds, Mr. Stone.

172
00:12:03,599 --> 00:12:05,126
I don't suppose
it matters to you,

173
00:12:05,200 --> 00:12:06,694
but my name isn't Stone.

174
00:12:08,304 --> 00:12:10,092
No?
No, it's Forsythe.

175
00:12:13,111 --> 00:12:15,500
Well, then,
that must be Stone there.

176
00:12:15,575 --> 00:12:18,428
That's very good, you know.
That's really very good.

177
00:12:18,493 --> 00:12:19,922
It's almost brilliant.

178
00:12:22,045 --> 00:12:24,466
Stone? I'm McGregor,
sent to meet you.

179
00:12:24,541 --> 00:12:26,451
That's very nice of you.

180
00:12:27,901 --> 00:12:29,330
Stone, meet Mister, uh...

181
00:12:29,405 --> 00:12:30,811
What did you say
your name was?

182
00:12:30,877 --> 00:12:32,087
Forsythe.

183
00:12:32,413 --> 00:12:34,300
Mr. Stone, Mr. Fort.

184
00:12:34,365 --> 00:12:37,755
We met on the train,
and the name is Forsythe.

185
00:12:38,436 --> 00:12:40,192
Too hot for Forsythe.

186
00:12:40,260 --> 00:12:43,561
Fort, Stone. Stone, Fort.

187
00:12:44,938 --> 00:12:47,240
Stone Fort.
And that's funny.

188
00:12:47,978 --> 00:12:51,239
If you two will hold onto each other,
I'll tend to your luggage.

189
00:12:55,786 --> 00:12:57,280
Pleasant chap.

190
00:12:57,802 --> 00:12:59,128
So friendly.

191
00:12:59,192 --> 00:13:00,461
Isn't he?

192
00:13:00,528 --> 00:13:01,903
Just what
I've always imagined

193
00:13:01,969 --> 00:13:04,390
a real officer
on the Frontier would be like.

194
00:13:06,737 --> 00:13:08,565
Well, my mother kept me
in the States

195
00:13:08,631 --> 00:13:10,518
untiI I made her send me
to Sandhurst.

196
00:13:10,583 --> 00:13:12,372
I've knocked about a bit
in the States.

197
00:13:12,439 --> 00:13:13,781
Scotch-Canadian, myself.

198
00:13:13,847 --> 00:13:16,214
What is this I'm in?
The Foreign Legion?

199
00:13:17,879 --> 00:13:20,246
I didn't even think my father knew
I was at Sandhurst,

200
00:13:20,311 --> 00:13:21,652
untiI this happened.

201
00:13:21,719 --> 00:13:22,856
What?

202
00:13:22,925 --> 00:13:24,884
His sending for me
to his regiment.

203
00:13:24,958 --> 00:13:25,940
Oh?

204
00:13:26,014 --> 00:13:28,283
Sort of, carry on
our tradition, you know?

205
00:13:36,964 --> 00:13:39,004
Naim Shah,
your servant, Stone.

206
00:13:40,100 --> 00:13:41,823
Ali Hamdi, yours.

207
00:13:43,363 --> 00:13:45,632
The night watchman,
the water carrier, the sweeper.

208
00:13:45,700 --> 00:13:47,463
You can hire
the rest of them later.

209
00:14:00,016 --> 00:14:01,577
Those things hurt my ears.

210
00:14:01,649 --> 00:14:02,631
That's odd.

211
00:14:02,705 --> 00:14:05,323
They sound to me
like a Scotch bagpipe.

212
00:14:12,600 --> 00:14:14,388
Your quarters, Stone.

213
00:14:29,086 --> 00:14:32,730
Pretty, huh? And soothing.
Thought I might entertain you.

214
00:14:32,797 --> 00:14:35,326
Wild Scotch airs.
Remind you of home.

215
00:14:36,356 --> 00:14:37,698
Your room.

216
00:14:39,301 --> 00:14:40,642
Someone deeded
all this junk

217
00:14:40,709 --> 00:14:42,596
to the South
Kensington Museum?

218
00:14:43,172 --> 00:14:45,889
That junk represents
the personal belongings

219
00:14:45,956 --> 00:14:47,872
of the man you're replacing.

220
00:14:47,947 --> 00:14:49,889
Killed on the border
last month.

221
00:14:49,963 --> 00:14:51,653
Oh, I'm sorry.

222
00:14:59,377 --> 00:15:02,192
Oh, McGregor, did my...

223
00:15:02,578 --> 00:15:05,927
Uh, the Colonel say anything
about what time he'd see me?

224
00:15:06,001 --> 00:15:08,904
No, he didn't. And my guess is
he won't see you till durbar.

225
00:15:08,977 --> 00:15:10,122
Oh.

226
00:15:10,193 --> 00:15:11,503
Don't let that
get you down.

227
00:15:11,570 --> 00:15:14,609
The old- The old man's
a stickler for red tape.

228
00:15:31,327 --> 00:15:34,196
Durbar. Bugles.

229
00:15:34,335 --> 00:15:37,368
And that's an order.
Ramrod.

230
00:15:42,277 --> 00:15:43,618
Durbar.

231
00:15:43,685 --> 00:15:46,303
Oh, a-already?
I'll be right with you.

232
00:15:47,214 --> 00:15:48,160
I want you to help me

233
00:15:48,236 --> 00:15:49,763
to keep them
in good condition.

234
00:15:50,060 --> 00:15:51,337
You keep then shined

235
00:15:51,404 --> 00:15:52,997
and I'II, uh,
keep them dirty.

236
00:15:53,580 --> 00:15:54,824
Durbar.

237
00:15:56,300 --> 00:15:58,187
Whenever you're ready,
sahib.

238
00:15:58,668 --> 00:16:00,456
Thanks,
old ColoniaI.

239
00:16:05,200 --> 00:16:06,574
Durbar, Barrett.

240
00:16:06,639 --> 00:16:08,330
Not today, old boy.

241
00:16:10,576 --> 00:16:11,828
Where to now?

242
00:16:11,895 --> 00:16:13,488
Over the border.

243
00:16:14,871 --> 00:16:16,594
I wish
I'd taken my mother's advice

244
00:16:16,663 --> 00:16:18,605
and joined the church
instead of the Army.

245
00:16:18,679 --> 00:16:19,857
I wish
I had the job.

246
00:16:19,927 --> 00:16:22,676
Does the Colonel think you're
the only one here who talks Pushtu?

247
00:16:22,742 --> 00:16:24,237
Who knows
what the Colonel thinks?

248
00:16:24,310 --> 00:16:27,278
I agree with you there.
Well, good luck.

249
00:16:27,767 --> 00:16:29,202
Thanks, Mac.

250
00:16:42,948 --> 00:16:44,890
Left wheel, turn!

251
00:16:47,267 --> 00:16:49,569
Left wheel, turn!

252
00:16:52,835 --> 00:16:54,664
Good head, eh? Yeah.

253
00:16:54,730 --> 00:16:56,071
How old is she, Major?

254
00:16:56,138 --> 00:16:57,381
Places, men.

255
00:16:58,538 --> 00:16:59,855
Good morning,
gentlemen.

256
00:16:59,921 --> 00:17:02,026
Good morning, sir.

257
00:17:33,150 --> 00:17:34,524
What's this?

258
00:17:36,318 --> 00:17:38,292
An Afridi Ghazi,
Colonel sahib.

259
00:17:38,365 --> 00:17:41,464
Caught in the quarters
of Capt. Norton, with this.

260
00:17:41,534 --> 00:17:42,843
Anything stolen?

261
00:17:42,911 --> 00:17:45,054
He meant to kill
Capt. Norton.

262
00:17:45,220 --> 00:17:48,424
Said Capt. Norton slept
with his feet toward Mecca.

263
00:17:50,634 --> 00:17:53,023
There are trees,
and we have rope.

264
00:17:53,258 --> 00:17:54,785
What have you got to say?

265
00:18:00,170 --> 00:18:01,250
Oh.

266
00:18:02,027 --> 00:18:04,034
Take him
and hang him to a tree,

267
00:18:04,107 --> 00:18:07,303
and then sew the dead body
in the skin of a pig.

268
00:18:21,847 --> 00:18:24,750
Well, that's what will happen
to him if he tries it again.

269
00:18:24,823 --> 00:18:26,285
You tell him that
and let him go.

270
00:18:33,086 --> 00:18:34,673
He doesn't seem to
like pigs.

271
00:18:34,742 --> 00:18:35,969
If that happened, in heaven

272
00:18:36,037 --> 00:18:38,906
he wouldn't get the 48 maidens
allotted by Allah.

273
00:18:38,981 --> 00:18:40,257
Tsk, tsk, tsk. Sad.

274
00:18:42,628 --> 00:18:43,806
Capt. Norton.

275
00:18:43,877 --> 00:18:45,568
Yes, sir?
Have you a compass?

276
00:18:45,637 --> 00:18:46,881
Yes, sir.

277
00:18:47,140 --> 00:18:49,115
Change the direction
of your bed.

278
00:18:49,189 --> 00:18:50,465
Yes, sir.

279
00:18:50,597 --> 00:18:52,124
Yes, that's all.

280
00:18:53,602 --> 00:18:55,064
Mr. McGregor.

281
00:18:56,291 --> 00:18:58,079
The two replacements?

282
00:18:58,915 --> 00:19:00,968
Mr. Forsythe,
from the Blues,

283
00:19:02,352 --> 00:19:04,294
Mr. Stone,
from Sandhurst.

284
00:19:05,680 --> 00:19:08,331
From the Blues, eh?
Quite so.

285
00:19:09,072 --> 00:19:11,560
Well, that's
a fashionable regiment.

286
00:19:11,632 --> 00:19:14,152
I am afraid, Mr. Forsythe,
you'll find us different.

287
00:19:14,224 --> 00:19:15,751
We have a reputation
as soldiers,

288
00:19:15,824 --> 00:19:17,067
and we're proud of it.

289
00:19:19,536 --> 00:19:20,878
Mr. Stone.

290
00:19:22,287 --> 00:19:24,308
You've come to us
direct from Sandhurst,

291
00:19:24,380 --> 00:19:26,290
without previous service.

292
00:19:26,365 --> 00:19:27,771
Is that correct?

293
00:19:27,837 --> 00:19:29,014
Yes, sir.

294
00:19:29,084 --> 00:19:32,183
Yes. Well, you've got
a great deal to learn.

295
00:19:32,893 --> 00:19:34,551
And I trust that you,

296
00:19:34,621 --> 00:19:36,693
and you, too,
Mr. Forsythe,

297
00:19:36,764 --> 00:19:38,903
will measure up
to our requirements.

298
00:19:39,388 --> 00:19:40,763
That's all, gentlemen.

299
00:19:53,098 --> 00:19:54,658
Crusty old...

300
00:19:55,658 --> 00:19:56,999
I'm sorry.

301
00:19:58,794 --> 00:20:00,834
Is it over?
Is that all?

302
00:20:01,449 --> 00:20:02,791
That's all.

303
00:20:08,490 --> 00:20:09,635
Lt. Stone.

304
00:20:09,706 --> 00:20:10,845
Yes, sir?

305
00:20:20,726 --> 00:20:21,970
The Colonel forgot something.

306
00:20:22,038 --> 00:20:23,467
I want you
to take this to him.

307
00:20:27,671 --> 00:20:28,947
Yes, sir.

308
00:20:38,077 --> 00:20:39,457
What's so funny?
You are.

309
00:20:40,548 --> 00:20:42,784
So the rough soldier
has a heart of gold.

310
00:20:43,876 --> 00:20:46,331
Never mind,
it comes out in all of us.

311
00:20:46,404 --> 00:20:47,386
It's the mother instinct.

312
00:21:09,329 --> 00:21:10,922
Is this it, sir?

313
00:21:11,728 --> 00:21:12,873
What?

314
00:21:23,896 --> 00:21:25,106
Where did you
get this?

315
00:21:25,176 --> 00:21:27,150
Mr. McGregor ordered me
to give it to you, sir.

316
00:21:27,223 --> 00:21:29,052
What infernal impudence!

317
00:21:29,118 --> 00:21:30,906
No, uh, not you.

318
00:21:31,677 --> 00:21:33,336
Not-not-not you.

319
00:21:34,429 --> 00:21:37,178
How's, uh,
How- H-How's your mother?

320
00:21:38,014 --> 00:21:39,258
Quite well, sir.

321
00:21:39,326 --> 00:21:40,700
Good, good.

322
00:21:40,990 --> 00:21:42,964
She always
hated the army.

323
00:21:43,325 --> 00:21:45,180
I- I don't understand
why she ever let you

324
00:21:45,245 --> 00:21:46,487
go through Sandhurst.

325
00:21:47,183 --> 00:21:48,514
She had to.

326
00:21:48,580 --> 00:21:51,580
I've kept after her about it
ever since I was so high.

327
00:21:51,652 --> 00:21:53,829
Oh? Wanted to be
a soldier, eh?

328
00:21:53,899 --> 00:21:56,452
We've always been soldiers,
for generations.

329
00:21:56,522 --> 00:21:57,766
Yes.

330
00:21:57,834 --> 00:22:00,322
Still, you're not one yet,
you know?

331
00:22:00,683 --> 00:22:01,959
Yes, sir.

332
00:22:02,122 --> 00:22:04,806
Really, you, uh,
you ought not to be here.

333
00:22:04,875 --> 00:22:06,817
Uh, not on the Frontier.

334
00:22:07,403 --> 00:22:08,897
But I am here, sir.

335
00:22:08,970 --> 00:22:11,598
Yes, but, uh,
don't try to take advantage.

336
00:22:11,667 --> 00:22:13,192
Don't expect
any favoritism.

337
00:22:13,265 --> 00:22:14,476
I don't, sir.

338
00:22:14,546 --> 00:22:16,913
I, uh,
I- I-I'm glad to see you,

339
00:22:16,978 --> 00:22:18,223
of course, and I...

340
00:22:18,292 --> 00:22:21,078
I'm sorry that the situation
makes any sort of,

341
00:22:21,143 --> 00:22:25,267
uh, o-of, uh,
social relation impossible.

342
00:22:27,927 --> 00:22:30,000
And I-I, uh...

343
00:22:30,135 --> 00:22:31,990
No, no, wait! W-wait.

344
00:22:32,055 --> 00:22:33,965
Uh, come back a moment.

345
00:22:35,966 --> 00:22:38,584
You see, uh,
this Frontier,

346
00:22:39,006 --> 00:22:40,894
it's not the same
as home service.

347
00:22:40,959 --> 00:22:42,366
No place for a Cub.

348
00:22:42,430 --> 00:22:44,476
A man's got
to be seasoned.

349
00:22:44,549 --> 00:22:46,687
You've got to start
from the bottom.

350
00:22:46,788 --> 00:22:49,657
Learn everything,
and if you don't measure up,

351
00:22:49,764 --> 00:22:50,876
out.

352
00:22:50,948 --> 00:22:52,858
The service
comes first.

353
00:22:53,860 --> 00:22:56,577
Something your mother
never understood.

354
00:22:57,252 --> 00:22:58,524
Yes, sir.

355
00:23:00,236 --> 00:23:01,610
Is that all, sir?

356
00:23:01,675 --> 00:23:03,977
What? Uh, uh, yes.

357
00:23:04,235 --> 00:23:06,952
Y- Yes, that's all.
That's all.

358
00:23:09,073 --> 00:23:10,961
I'm very glad to see...

359
00:23:27,001 --> 00:23:28,245
Poor kid.

360
00:23:28,665 --> 00:23:30,639
I thought
if I got them alone...

361
00:23:31,193 --> 00:23:33,719
But the old man
has ice-water in his veins.

362
00:23:33,790 --> 00:23:35,481
You don't know
the colonel, McGregor.

363
00:23:35,550 --> 00:23:36,760
Neither do you.

364
00:23:36,830 --> 00:23:38,456
Mr. McGregor.
Yes, sir.

365
00:23:38,527 --> 00:23:41,210
As I remarked to one of
my other officers this morning,

366
00:23:41,278 --> 00:23:44,278
there is no place for
sentimentality in the Army.

367
00:23:44,702 --> 00:23:46,293
Neither sentimentality

368
00:23:46,363 --> 00:23:48,480
nor impertinence,
Mr. McGregor.

369
00:24:05,836 --> 00:24:07,079
Stone.

370
00:24:12,658 --> 00:24:14,992
Interesting, the durbar,
isn't it?

371
00:24:15,634 --> 00:24:17,292
I'm sorry
I sent you in there.

372
00:24:17,362 --> 00:24:18,824
I should have known better.

373
00:24:18,899 --> 00:24:20,786
Should have known
how he'd treat you.

374
00:24:20,850 --> 00:24:22,225
What's a son to him,

375
00:24:22,290 --> 00:24:23,637
compared to
his blasted regiment?

376
00:24:23,705 --> 00:24:24,882
Martinet. Ramrod.

377
00:24:24,952 --> 00:24:26,513
That's what he is.
Everybody knows it.

378
00:24:26,585 --> 00:24:27,926
You might as well
get used to it.

379
00:24:27,992 --> 00:24:29,487
That's a lie.

380
00:24:32,056 --> 00:24:33,168
I'm sorry,

381
00:24:33,240 --> 00:24:35,455
I can't keep my mouth shut.
That's my trouble.

382
00:24:36,831 --> 00:24:39,133
Biggest fooI in the Army.
I'm sorry.

383
00:24:40,575 --> 00:24:42,517
That's all-
all right, Mac.

384
00:24:46,591 --> 00:24:50,972
" Sure I love the dear silver
that shines in her hair "

385
00:24:51,205 --> 00:24:53,409
" And the brow
that's all furrowed "

386
00:24:53,477 --> 00:24:55,038
" and wrinkled with care "

387
00:24:58,903 --> 00:25:02,689
" Oh, God bless you
and keep you "

388
00:25:02,764 --> 00:25:04,936
" Mother McGregor "

389
00:25:12,525 --> 00:25:15,378
Now, when a troop wheels
on the move,

390
00:25:15,794 --> 00:25:17,834
what do the troop leaders
look out for?

391
00:25:17,970 --> 00:25:19,464
Mr. Stone,
I asked you a question.

392
00:25:19,538 --> 00:25:20,520
Yes, sir.

393
00:25:23,388 --> 00:25:25,938
Come on, come on, come on.
Come on.

394
00:25:27,481 --> 00:25:28,626
Got it all that time.

395
00:25:28,697 --> 00:25:29,646
All right.

396
00:25:43,135 --> 00:25:45,622
Bedding should be
changed, Mr. Stone.

397
00:25:46,235 --> 00:25:48,124
Yes, I see now,
Risaldar Major.

398
00:25:48,678 --> 00:25:50,783
We don't have these
beastly ticks in England.

399
00:25:53,094 --> 00:25:55,909
Sergeant, have this
horse's shoe attended to.

400
00:25:58,822 --> 00:26:00,415
Come on!

401
00:26:09,868 --> 00:26:12,014
Give him a good walk
while he cools off.

402
00:26:19,219 --> 00:26:20,680
A good man, Forsythe.

403
00:26:20,755 --> 00:26:22,315
Jump!

404
00:26:23,667 --> 00:26:25,390
See the way
he took that jump?

405
00:26:25,459 --> 00:26:27,914
Yes, they teach them
to jump in the Blues.

406
00:26:27,987 --> 00:26:29,586
Yes. Yes, what?

407
00:26:30,553 --> 00:26:31,633
Oh.

408
00:26:38,912 --> 00:26:40,373
Good work, Forsythe.

409
00:26:40,448 --> 00:26:41,975
Thank you, sir.

410
00:26:43,424 --> 00:26:46,107
Mr. McGregor,
you're improperly dressed.

411
00:26:46,272 --> 00:26:47,516
I'm sorry, sir.

412
00:26:58,240 --> 00:26:59,977
That was a nice jump
you made, Mac.

413
00:27:00,045 --> 00:27:01,256
Thanks.
Hello, Stone.

414
00:27:01,325 --> 00:27:02,273
Hello.

415
00:27:02,349 --> 00:27:03,942
Remarkable man,
your father.

416
00:27:04,013 --> 00:27:05,988
Knows a good soldier
when he sees one.

417
00:27:06,445 --> 00:27:08,234
Appreciates neatness, too.

418
00:27:09,485 --> 00:27:11,143
Well,
how about a spot of scotch?

419
00:27:11,565 --> 00:27:13,987
Thanks. I haven't finished
inspection yet.

420
00:27:14,317 --> 00:27:17,066
Ten minutes for their backs
and five for their bellies.

421
00:27:17,133 --> 00:27:19,211
That's the order
of grooming.

422
00:27:20,051 --> 00:27:22,054
Very touching,
the lad's devotion.

423
00:27:22,662 --> 00:27:25,367
Must warm the maternaI
cockles of your heart.

424
00:27:25,434 --> 00:27:26,547
Eh, McGregor?

425
00:27:33,178 --> 00:27:35,633
What about pulling
a few pegs with me, huh?

426
00:27:36,666 --> 00:27:38,192
I'm in favor of it.
Let's go.

427
00:27:38,266 --> 00:27:39,957
Well, uh,
how about 10 Rupees?

428
00:27:40,026 --> 00:27:41,041
Make it 20.

429
00:27:46,675 --> 00:27:47,557
Ready?

430
00:27:47,623 --> 00:27:48,703
Whenever you say.

431
00:28:08,492 --> 00:28:10,241
They should make
those pegs smaller.

432
00:28:10,308 --> 00:28:11,786
Be more sport to it,
huh?

433
00:28:13,268 --> 00:28:16,301
" Oh, he flew
through the air "

434
00:28:16,372 --> 00:28:18,227
" With the greatest
of ease "

435
00:28:18,292 --> 00:28:22,253
" And the daring young man
owes me 20 Rupees "

436
00:28:44,577 --> 00:28:46,300
Have some tea, Stone?

437
00:28:46,369 --> 00:28:47,776
No, thanks.

438
00:28:57,505 --> 00:28:59,179
Call it for first
in the bath.

439
00:28:59,248 --> 00:29:00,174
Heads.

440
00:29:00,238 --> 00:29:01,186
Right.

441
00:29:01,742 --> 00:29:03,946
You fellows bathe
to keep cooI

442
00:29:04,174 --> 00:29:06,508
and I bathe
because I badly need it.

443
00:29:30,235 --> 00:29:31,413
Every time I do this

444
00:29:31,483 --> 00:29:33,239
I remind myself
of my old man.

445
00:29:33,307 --> 00:29:34,452
Whiskers.

446
00:29:36,155 --> 00:29:37,944
He was a crabby old cuss.

447
00:29:38,138 --> 00:29:40,244
Back in Alberta
I had a colt once.

448
00:29:41,179 --> 00:29:43,066
Lot of class and nerve.

449
00:29:43,579 --> 00:29:45,368
You could tell
he was no carthorse

450
00:29:45,435 --> 00:29:46,824
when he was a yearling.

451
00:29:47,522 --> 00:29:49,600
The old man hooked him
to a plow.

452
00:29:50,888 --> 00:29:52,677
Took all the spirit
out of him.

453
00:29:53,479 --> 00:29:55,519
He broke him in,
as he said he would

454
00:29:55,592 --> 00:29:57,829
and I never forgave him
for it.

455
00:29:57,896 --> 00:30:00,613
I don't think the horse
ever did realize what...

456
00:30:00,680 --> 00:30:02,752
what the old man
did to him.

457
00:30:03,592 --> 00:30:05,217
So I'm the horse.

458
00:30:05,800 --> 00:30:07,393
Very subtle, Mac.

459
00:30:07,816 --> 00:30:09,245
What the blazes do you mean?

460
00:30:09,320 --> 00:30:11,367
I'm no two-year-old. I'm 21.

461
00:30:11,919 --> 00:30:14,292
And if anybody thinks
my old man's going to break my nerve-

462
00:30:14,357 --> 00:30:16,659
What are you talking about?
I wasn't thinking of you at all.

463
00:30:16,725 --> 00:30:18,067
And let me tell
you another thing,

464
00:30:18,133 --> 00:30:20,850
I don't need a nurse.
Now you can go on shaving.

465
00:30:25,748 --> 00:30:27,571
Have a little soap.
You need it.

466
00:30:46,434 --> 00:30:47,995
Do you have to do that?

467
00:30:48,513 --> 00:30:51,579
Why, like you, I have
a softer side to my nature.

468
00:30:51,874 --> 00:30:55,005
It finds its outlet in music.
See? The scales.

469
00:30:55,170 --> 00:30:57,177
Hey, Mac, get me a towel,
will you?

470
00:31:00,841 --> 00:31:02,728
Variations,
one hand, Mac.

471
00:31:03,049 --> 00:31:04,516
Listen, Forsythe.

472
00:31:04,591 --> 00:31:07,690
This Mother Machree business
has gone far enough.

473
00:31:08,591 --> 00:31:10,118
Why, of course, Mac.

474
00:31:10,191 --> 00:31:12,100
I'm sorry.
I didn't realize it.

475
00:31:12,239 --> 00:31:15,174
Well, let's, uh,
just forget all about it. Hm?

476
00:31:15,247 --> 00:31:16,261
Thanks.

477
00:31:16,334 --> 00:31:18,025
Hey, Mac,
that soap's in my eyes.

478
00:31:18,095 --> 00:31:20,102
Give me a towel,
will you?

479
00:31:50,754 --> 00:31:51,998
McGregor.

480
00:32:03,625 --> 00:32:05,730
Variations, two hands, Mac.

481
00:32:36,092 --> 00:32:38,198
How long are you
going to...

482
00:32:42,781 --> 00:32:44,216
Keep playing.

483
00:32:45,507 --> 00:32:48,670
Variations, Mr. Forsythe,
with both hands.

484
00:32:51,011 --> 00:32:52,604
Cobras have
a softer side, too.

485
00:32:52,674 --> 00:32:53,689
Finds an outlet in music.

486
00:32:53,763 --> 00:32:55,835
Of course,
if you-if you stop playing,

487
00:32:57,187 --> 00:32:59,529
You know, you might live
a couple of hours.

488
00:32:59,594 --> 00:33:02,343
I had a friend once
that lived for two days.

489
00:33:03,114 --> 00:33:04,902
Try it with one hand.

490
00:33:10,096 --> 00:33:11,241
Mac!

491
00:33:29,079 --> 00:33:31,413
Allow me.
You might spill it.

492
00:33:38,173 --> 00:33:39,766
For sale, cheap.

493
00:33:40,189 --> 00:33:42,523
One secondhand
musical instrument.

494
00:33:47,844 --> 00:33:49,153
200 feet more.

495
00:33:49,220 --> 00:33:50,747
Plus 200 east.

496
00:33:51,140 --> 00:33:53,986
Elevation, 300.

497
00:33:54,051 --> 00:33:55,458
Mr. McGregor.
Yes, sir?

498
00:33:55,524 --> 00:33:57,466
There's no word
yet from Barrett.

499
00:33:57,539 --> 00:33:59,204
We must get in touch with him.
Yes, sir.

500
00:33:59,274 --> 00:34:00,932
You're familiar
with the roads north east

501
00:34:01,002 --> 00:34:01,984
of Fort Jamrud?

502
00:34:02,058 --> 00:34:03,585
I am, sir.
Yes, good, good.

503
00:34:03,657 --> 00:34:05,316
You'll cross
the Frontier tonight.

504
00:34:05,386 --> 00:34:06,727
Take one subaltern,

505
00:34:06,793 --> 00:34:10,291
one NCO, 10 men,
four spare horses.

506
00:34:10,647 --> 00:34:12,463
And, uh, rifles.

507
00:34:13,009 --> 00:34:14,219
Not lances.

508
00:34:14,288 --> 00:34:15,303
I see, sir.

509
00:34:15,504 --> 00:34:18,057
Ostensibly,
a hunting expedition.

510
00:34:18,193 --> 00:34:19,916
What subaltern
shall I take, sir?

511
00:34:19,985 --> 00:34:21,327
Mmm,
any preference?

512
00:34:22,609 --> 00:34:23,859
Mr. Stone, sir.

513
00:34:25,558 --> 00:34:27,980
No service experience.
Take Morgan.

514
00:34:28,119 --> 00:34:29,329
He's on leave, sir.

515
00:34:29,398 --> 00:34:30,773
Well, then, take Forsythe.

516
00:34:31,414 --> 00:34:32,363
Yes, sir.

517
00:34:32,438 --> 00:34:33,835
Here are your orders.

518
00:34:35,678 --> 00:34:37,947
And this time,
obey them.

519
00:34:38,238 --> 00:34:39,350
Yes, sir.

520
00:34:45,149 --> 00:34:46,164
Forsythe.

521
00:34:46,238 --> 00:34:47,186
Huh?

522
00:34:48,772 --> 00:34:50,681
We're leaving for
the border immediately.

523
00:34:50,755 --> 00:34:51,803
What?

524
00:34:53,668 --> 00:34:54,715
Action?

525
00:34:55,428 --> 00:34:56,442
Can't say.

526
00:34:56,515 --> 00:34:57,458
Oh.

527
00:34:57,534 --> 00:34:59,140
We leave
for the border?

528
00:34:59,851 --> 00:35:02,600
Uh, small expedition.
Only one junior officer.

529
00:35:03,851 --> 00:35:05,127
Forsythe.
Yes?

530
00:35:05,323 --> 00:35:07,046
One junior officer,
so he had to choose-

531
00:35:07,114 --> 00:35:08,675
I chose Forsythe.

532
00:35:10,378 --> 00:35:11,523
I see.

533
00:35:21,419 --> 00:35:22,390
Sir.

534
00:35:22,463 --> 00:35:24,114
What do you mean by
intruding like this?

535
00:35:24,184 --> 00:35:25,907
Why wasn't I chosen
to go with McGregor?

536
00:35:25,975 --> 00:35:27,797
Are you questioning
my orders?

537
00:35:27,928 --> 00:35:29,488
Then it was your orders.

538
00:35:29,559 --> 00:35:31,282
It wasn't McGregor's choice.
It was yours.

539
00:35:31,352 --> 00:35:32,279
Mr. Stone.

540
00:35:32,343 --> 00:35:33,870
I came out to India
to be an officer,

541
00:35:33,944 --> 00:35:35,253
and I've been given
things to do

542
00:35:35,319 --> 00:35:37,229
I learned in my first year
at Sandhurst.

543
00:35:37,303 --> 00:35:39,960
I haven't asked any favors,
and I'm not asking any now.

544
00:35:40,029 --> 00:35:41,590
But if you meant to
treat me this way,

545
00:35:41,661 --> 00:35:43,156
why did you
bring me out here?

546
00:35:43,325 --> 00:35:44,852
Why did you send for me?

547
00:35:44,925 --> 00:35:46,402
I didn't send for you.

548
00:35:46,538 --> 00:35:47,994
Y- you didn't?

549
00:35:50,308 --> 00:35:51,323
Oh.

550
00:36:22,770 --> 00:36:24,810
Are you aware
we're being shot at?

551
00:36:26,673 --> 00:36:27,818
We camp here.

552
00:36:27,889 --> 00:36:29,553
This is no place to camp.

553
00:36:40,862 --> 00:36:42,106
Are you
out of your mind?

554
00:36:42,174 --> 00:36:44,313
They'll rush us in the night
and slit our throats.

555
00:36:44,382 --> 00:36:46,455
This can't be
what the Colonel meant.

556
00:36:46,526 --> 00:36:48,566
Easy to see how much
you learned in the Blues

557
00:36:48,638 --> 00:36:49,718
about Frontier fighting.

558
00:37:01,451 --> 00:37:02,629
No firing.

559
00:37:03,179 --> 00:37:04,488
He's mine.

560
00:37:08,396 --> 00:37:09,573
Rapid fire!

561
00:37:22,242 --> 00:37:24,120
You just missed my ear, Mac.

562
00:37:24,312 --> 00:37:25,457
You're lucky, Barrett.

563
00:37:25,528 --> 00:37:26,738
You got a cigarette?

564
00:37:26,808 --> 00:37:27,823
Yeah.

565
00:37:30,648 --> 00:37:31,663
Thanks.

566
00:37:32,121 --> 00:37:33,811
What shall I tell
the ColoneI?

567
00:37:35,096 --> 00:37:36,525
Mohammed Khan,

568
00:37:37,560 --> 00:37:40,277
is effecting a coalition
of all the tribes.

569
00:37:42,649 --> 00:37:45,807
But don't forget, Colonel,
GopaI's a friendly state.

570
00:37:46,127 --> 00:37:48,964
The Emir's our friend,
as who knows better than you.

571
00:37:49,061 --> 00:37:51,745
Oh, of course, I've known
Othman Ali for 20 years.

572
00:37:51,814 --> 00:37:53,275
Every year or so
I take the regiment

573
00:37:53,349 --> 00:37:55,716
up to Gopal for
maneuvers and pig-sticking.

574
00:37:55,845 --> 00:37:58,398
He's got the best wild pig
north of the Ganges.

575
00:37:58,469 --> 00:37:59,418
Ah.

576
00:37:59,494 --> 00:38:01,949
But two million
rounds of ammunition.

577
00:38:02,022 --> 00:38:03,199
Oh, no, Woodley.

578
00:38:03,269 --> 00:38:05,538
Why, that's enough
to start a small-sized war.

579
00:38:05,829 --> 00:38:08,163
And then, who knows?

580
00:38:11,026 --> 00:38:13,263
Yes, who knows?

581
00:38:15,666 --> 00:38:17,324
But he asked for it.

582
00:38:17,586 --> 00:38:20,848
And if we refused, well,
he mightn't be our friend.

583
00:38:20,914 --> 00:38:22,474
And so he gets it, eh?
Yes.

584
00:38:23,762 --> 00:38:24,907
McGregor, Sahib.

585
00:38:24,978 --> 00:38:26,505
Oh, ask Mr. McGregor
to come in.

586
00:38:26,578 --> 00:38:28,072
Oh, sit down, sir,
won't you?

587
00:38:36,607 --> 00:38:38,363
You saw Barrett?
Yes, sir.

588
00:38:38,431 --> 00:38:41,278
He reports Mohammed Khan
is trying to stir up all the border tribes,

589
00:38:41,344 --> 00:38:42,904
and effect
a coalition of all of them.

590
00:38:42,975 --> 00:38:44,764
They're listening
to him as he's promised

591
00:38:44,832 --> 00:38:46,392
to supply them
with machine guns,

592
00:38:46,463 --> 00:38:47,990
and two million
rounds of ammunition.

593
00:38:48,064 --> 00:38:49,176
Ammunition?

594
00:38:49,536 --> 00:38:51,740
Oh, that's good work.
Thank you, McGregor.

595
00:38:51,808 --> 00:38:53,237
Thank Barrett, sir.

596
00:38:56,512 --> 00:38:58,915
Look at here, sir, I-I know
it's none of my business,

597
00:38:58,988 --> 00:39:00,330
but couldn't we
slip out of here,

598
00:39:00,396 --> 00:39:02,501
a small detachment of us,
anyway, on our own?

599
00:39:02,605 --> 00:39:04,099
Try to get a chance
at him, kill him,

600
00:39:04,173 --> 00:39:06,278
and-and nip the whole
business in the bud?

601
00:39:06,989 --> 00:39:08,298
Are you suggesting

602
00:39:08,365 --> 00:39:10,885
that I should commence
hostilities without orders?

603
00:39:11,180 --> 00:39:13,068
And, uh, ahem,
without reporting this

604
00:39:13,132 --> 00:39:14,212
to the Intelligence?

605
00:39:14,284 --> 00:39:16,706
Intelligence, those fools.
General staff?

606
00:39:16,780 --> 00:39:19,169
You know, sir, they'll send us
anywhere but into action.

607
00:39:19,244 --> 00:39:21,913
To Gopal to stick pigs
for instance, like last summer.

608
00:39:21,982 --> 00:39:23,766
An excellent suggestion.

609
00:39:26,426 --> 00:39:28,313
Sir Thomas,
Mr. McGregor.

610
00:39:29,206 --> 00:39:32,784
Mr. McGregor, Maj. Gen.
Sir Thomas Woodley.

611
00:39:33,941 --> 00:39:37,008
Chief of Intelligence.
Army Headquarters.

612
00:39:38,133 --> 00:39:39,443
Mr. McGregor.

613
00:39:42,517 --> 00:39:45,859
CoI. Stone, your regiment
will leave at dawn for GopaI.

614
00:39:46,282 --> 00:39:47,480
Yes, sir.

615
00:39:47,581 --> 00:39:49,658
Now, get yourself
a couple of hours sleep.

616
00:39:49,730 --> 00:39:51,039
We leave at 6:00.

617
00:39:52,450 --> 00:39:53,595
Yes, sir.

618
00:39:54,114 --> 00:39:55,641
Wish I could go with you.

619
00:39:55,715 --> 00:39:57,242
I always liked pig-sticking.

620
00:39:57,314 --> 00:39:58,329
Pig-sticking.

621
00:39:58,947 --> 00:40:01,500
Well, I seem to remember
feeling that way once.

622
00:40:01,571 --> 00:40:02,553
He's probably right.

623
00:40:02,627 --> 00:40:03,575
Hm.

624
00:40:03,650 --> 00:40:05,210
But he brought
our answer, Stone.

625
00:40:05,282 --> 00:40:08,129
A plain two and two
that makes a very plain four.

626
00:40:08,899 --> 00:40:12,289
Mohammed Khan needs
two million rounds of ammunition.

627
00:40:12,362 --> 00:40:14,986
And the Emir of Gopal asks us
for two million rounds-

628
00:40:15,055 --> 00:40:17,226
Yes, yes, and it's not
difficult to guess,

629
00:40:17,295 --> 00:40:19,946
that Mohammed Khan persuaded
the Emir to ask for it.

630
00:40:20,015 --> 00:40:22,382
He knows we'll have
to let him have it, too.

631
00:40:22,479 --> 00:40:24,846
And GopaI's not only remote,

632
00:40:24,975 --> 00:40:28,041
but far enough removed
from the Khan's home fires,

633
00:40:28,111 --> 00:40:29,704
that we shouldn't
be suspicious.

634
00:40:29,775 --> 00:40:31,336
Very pretty, indeed.

635
00:40:31,407 --> 00:40:33,412
And it becomes
our very pleasant job,

636
00:40:33,484 --> 00:40:34,682
to see that the Emir

637
00:40:34,750 --> 00:40:36,498
really is the one
who gets the ammunition.

638
00:40:37,142 --> 00:40:38,320
That old pussy-footer

639
00:40:38,390 --> 00:40:40,306
gets paid for
being intelligent.

640
00:40:40,541 --> 00:40:42,908
I tell you, Forsythe,
everything's going to smash.

641
00:40:42,972 --> 00:40:43,920
What?

642
00:40:43,996 --> 00:40:44,923
Pig-sticking.

643
00:40:44,989 --> 00:40:47,771
We're going to ride all around Gopal
sticking toothpicks into pigs.

644
00:40:47,836 --> 00:40:49,396
Sounds rather fun.

645
00:40:49,468 --> 00:40:51,705
I ought to be rather good
at that, don't you think?

646
00:40:51,772 --> 00:40:52,852
Hmm.

647
00:40:52,924 --> 00:40:55,706
By the way, McGregor,
I've got bad news for you.

648
00:40:56,124 --> 00:40:59,299
Your ward needs
parental controI, I fear.

649
00:40:59,366 --> 00:41:00,607
That is, if you can find him.

650
00:41:00,676 --> 00:41:03,393
Naim Shah tells me he's been
out every night since we left.

651
00:41:03,459 --> 00:41:05,537
Rolling home
to quarters blotto.

652
00:41:05,609 --> 00:41:07,682
Tonight he's still
out on a binge.

653
00:41:10,057 --> 00:41:13,188
Hm. We leave for
Gopal in two hours.

654
00:41:13,673 --> 00:41:16,739
Oh, without Stone, it appears.

655
00:41:16,841 --> 00:41:19,809
My, what will
the stern father say?

656
00:41:21,381 --> 00:41:23,629
You'd better do
something about it, Mac.

657
00:41:23,728 --> 00:41:25,005
The young fooI.

658
00:41:25,072 --> 00:41:27,079
Let old Ramrod do
what he likes with his son.

659
00:41:27,152 --> 00:41:29,547
It's no concern of mine.
I'm going to bed.

660
00:41:30,582 --> 00:41:31,891
So am I.

661
00:41:54,851 --> 00:41:55,899
What are you doing here?

662
00:41:55,972 --> 00:41:58,175
The same as you are.
Looking for him.

663
00:41:58,244 --> 00:41:59,934
And I wish you'd be
honest with yourself,

664
00:42:00,003 --> 00:42:02,175
and let me know
what you're really going to do.

665
00:42:02,243 --> 00:42:04,828
If you'd just tell me,
maybe I'd get more sleep.

666
00:42:07,203 --> 00:42:09,110
Now that we are here,

667
00:42:09,184 --> 00:42:11,335
what would you do
if you were drunk?

668
00:42:11,594 --> 00:42:12,707
How drunk?

669
00:42:13,354 --> 00:42:14,598
Pretty drunk.

670
00:42:15,274 --> 00:42:17,161
I'd go looking
for that music.

671
00:42:23,760 --> 00:42:25,036
Come on, speed it up, Stone,

672
00:42:25,105 --> 00:42:26,631
or we'll all be
doing stable duty.

673
00:42:26,704 --> 00:42:28,592
I can take care of myself.

674
00:42:28,816 --> 00:42:29,928
Come along, Casanova,

675
00:42:30,000 --> 00:42:31,495
these will make
a new man of you.

676
00:43:11,626 --> 00:43:13,033
Forgot something.

677
00:43:13,290 --> 00:43:15,013
I thought you
might get lonesome.

678
00:43:15,082 --> 00:43:16,741
Get yourself a cobra.

679
00:43:35,671 --> 00:43:37,875
The welcoming committee
from the Emir.

680
00:43:44,949 --> 00:43:47,100
That's his vizier,
bringing gifts

681
00:43:47,169 --> 00:43:49,883
for the ColoneI
from his old paI.

682
00:43:55,934 --> 00:43:56,916
His Highness,

683
00:43:56,990 --> 00:43:58,746
Othman Ali Bahadur,
Emir of Gopal,

684
00:43:58,814 --> 00:44:01,787
bids welcome to his friends
and allies of the Raj.

685
00:44:01,860 --> 00:44:03,038
Welcome, huzoor,

686
00:44:03,108 --> 00:44:05,082
thrice welcome,
in the name of Allah.

687
00:44:05,156 --> 00:44:07,044
Convey my thanks
to your master,

688
00:44:07,108 --> 00:44:08,668
ahem, my old friend.

689
00:44:09,025 --> 00:44:11,654
Uh, m-may he live
a thousand years.

690
00:44:11,723 --> 00:44:14,440
His Highness orders me
to express his wish, huzoor,

691
00:44:14,507 --> 00:44:17,540
that you may live long enough
to be present at his funeraI.

692
00:44:17,611 --> 00:44:19,466
Uh, oh, yes, quite so.
Quite so.

693
00:44:19,691 --> 00:44:21,633
He went the old man
one better that time.

694
00:44:21,707 --> 00:44:23,780
Wicked looking birds,
aren't they?

695
00:44:24,945 --> 00:44:26,603
Hunting falcons, Forsythe.

696
00:44:26,769 --> 00:44:28,013
Swiftest thing in the air.

697
00:44:28,081 --> 00:44:29,608
Full of fight
and trained to kill,

698
00:44:29,681 --> 00:44:31,950
like the rest of these
mangy-looking fellows.

699
00:44:32,017 --> 00:44:34,617
A long-legged man
is always full of wind.

700
00:44:36,920 --> 00:44:38,130
Barrett.

701
00:44:41,336 --> 00:44:43,158
His Highness
invites you, huzoor,

702
00:44:43,224 --> 00:44:45,559
and all the officer sahibs,
to an entertainment

703
00:44:45,624 --> 00:44:47,151
in your honor,
tonight at the palace.

704
00:44:47,224 --> 00:44:49,300
I accept on their
behalf with pleasure.

705
00:44:49,373 --> 00:44:51,130
All my thanks
to His Highness.

706
00:45:18,507 --> 00:45:20,165
His Highness awaits you.

707
00:45:24,017 --> 00:45:25,927
Salaam, Colonel Sahib.

708
00:45:26,002 --> 00:45:27,627
Salaam, Your Highness.

709
00:45:36,594 --> 00:45:39,764
May I present the officers of the 41st
Bengal Lancers, Your Highness?

710
00:45:43,223 --> 00:45:45,928
My poor hovel is yours,
sahiban.

711
00:45:45,995 --> 00:45:48,404
Everything here
is for your pleasure.

712
00:45:48,703 --> 00:45:50,526
Please enjoy yourselves.

713
00:45:52,447 --> 00:45:54,486
Now, this is what
army life should be.

714
00:45:54,559 --> 00:45:55,934
Like the Arabian Nights,
isn't it?

715
00:45:55,999 --> 00:45:57,787
Anything like this
in Canada, Mac?

716
00:45:57,855 --> 00:45:59,283
Quite a teepee, huh?

717
00:46:11,627 --> 00:46:13,929
I sent to London
for that, and you-

718
00:46:22,444 --> 00:46:25,673
My two good friends.
My guest, CoI. Stone.

719
00:46:26,124 --> 00:46:28,034
My guest, Mohammed Khan.

720
00:46:28,364 --> 00:46:30,312
Very glad to
know you Khan sahib.

721
00:46:30,386 --> 00:46:31,946
At last, CoI. Stone.

722
00:46:33,291 --> 00:46:35,891
We almost met once before,
did we not, you and I?

723
00:46:35,960 --> 00:46:39,059
Yes, I-I believe we did.
Just missed you, didn't I?

724
00:46:39,129 --> 00:46:41,431
A blind man wants
nothing except his eyes.

725
00:46:42,585 --> 00:46:44,177
That's an Afghan proverb.

726
00:46:44,952 --> 00:46:46,643
And now,
if you will forgive me,

727
00:46:46,713 --> 00:46:48,852
I must leave
my two good friends together.

728
00:46:48,921 --> 00:46:50,776
I must go to see
my other guests.

729
00:46:50,841 --> 00:46:51,888
Oh, yes,
Your Highness.

730
00:46:51,961 --> 00:46:54,267
No doubt that Khan and I
will find much to talk about.

731
00:46:55,647 --> 00:46:56,724
Highness.

732
00:46:57,462 --> 00:46:59,748
You were not expected
with your lancers.

733
00:47:00,102 --> 00:47:01,760
A hasty trip, wasn't it?

734
00:47:01,830 --> 00:47:03,171
In search of, uh...

735
00:47:03,238 --> 00:47:04,350
Pigs.

736
00:47:08,646 --> 00:47:10,107
There's another proverb:

737
00:47:10,182 --> 00:47:13,531
The little jackal barks,
but the caravan passes.

738
00:47:15,174 --> 00:47:16,930
Won't you sit down,
CoI. Stone?

739
00:47:17,638 --> 00:47:18,717
Yes.

740
00:47:26,003 --> 00:47:27,279
I say, look.

741
00:47:35,539 --> 00:47:36,848
I saw her first.

742
00:47:36,914 --> 00:47:38,638
No, no, no,
no, no, no, Mac.

743
00:47:39,667 --> 00:47:41,325
A direct frontal attack?

744
00:47:41,395 --> 00:47:44,048
That's the wrong tactics.
This requires finesse.

745
00:47:48,863 --> 00:47:51,318
I'll toss you.
The loser stays clear.

746
00:47:53,248 --> 00:47:54,557
Right you are.

747
00:47:57,312 --> 00:47:58,359
Heads.

748
00:48:01,312 --> 00:48:02,905
Now watch closely.

749
00:48:10,801 --> 00:48:13,666
Well, uh, go ahead.
Uh, I'm watching you closely.

750
00:48:17,036 --> 00:48:18,214
Gentlemen.

751
00:48:18,477 --> 00:48:21,030
Uh, two more of my officers
I should like you to meet.

752
00:48:21,101 --> 00:48:22,759
Mr. McGregor, Mr. Forsythe.

753
00:48:22,829 --> 00:48:25,480
This is our friend
and neighbor, Mohammed Khan.

754
00:48:27,309 --> 00:48:29,065
A great pleasure,
gentlemen.

755
00:48:34,080 --> 00:48:36,245
Let me give you some
advice, Mr. Forsythe.

756
00:48:36,377 --> 00:48:38,450
Never make fun of
military Intelligence.

757
00:48:38,586 --> 00:48:40,790
Thank you very much.
And now-

758
00:48:40,858 --> 00:48:42,068
Uh, wait a minute.

759
00:48:43,482 --> 00:48:45,173
That girI and...

760
00:48:46,810 --> 00:48:48,817
I've got some things
to find out.

761
00:48:53,466 --> 00:48:55,538
He plans to leave
tomorrow morning.

762
00:48:55,866 --> 00:48:58,563
I knew he would
as soon as we got here.

763
00:48:59,204 --> 00:49:01,246
We must keep him
here if possible.

764
00:49:01,318 --> 00:49:02,464
I was right.

765
00:49:02,534 --> 00:49:03,876
She came here
with Mohammed Khan.

766
00:49:03,942 --> 00:49:05,950
Aha, so that's how it is.

767
00:49:06,022 --> 00:49:08,161
Diplomatic complications
rear their heads, huh?

768
00:49:08,231 --> 00:49:09,758
Looks like it.
We'd better find them.

769
00:49:09,831 --> 00:49:12,002
Mac, I've been thinking.

770
00:49:12,071 --> 00:49:14,176
I'm very fond
of you, you know.

771
00:49:15,591 --> 00:49:18,242
I have a feeling this is
going to cost me something.

772
00:49:18,311 --> 00:49:19,740
Oh, no, Mac.

773
