our plans in any respect.

1027
01:07:11,845 --> 01:07:13,885
But-But knowing where
he's taking your son

1028
01:07:13,957 --> 01:07:15,167
makes all
the difference, sir.

1029
01:07:15,237 --> 01:07:17,277
We can be at Mogala
almost as soon as he is.

1030
01:07:17,349 --> 01:07:19,035
This regiment
can ride, sir.

1031
01:07:20,334 --> 01:07:22,468
I'm aware
my regiment can ride.

1032
01:07:22,889 --> 01:07:24,995
I'm also aware that
I am not going to do

1033
01:07:25,066 --> 01:07:28,229
precisely what Mohammed Khan
has planned that I should do.

1034
01:07:28,298 --> 01:07:30,567
He took my son
to goad me into pursuing him

1035
01:07:30,634 --> 01:07:32,805
to draw the lancers
from their position.

1036
01:07:32,874 --> 01:07:34,248
He's mistaken his man.

1037
01:07:34,314 --> 01:07:36,004
But this-
In our present position,

1038
01:07:36,073 --> 01:07:38,375
the regiment holds
Mohammed Khan checkmate.

1039
01:07:38,441 --> 01:07:39,783
The regiment stays here.

1040
01:07:39,849 --> 01:07:40,864
Then let me go.

1041
01:07:40,937 --> 01:07:41,880
I can take
a small detachment-

1042
01:07:41,955 --> 01:07:43,773
Mr. McGregor, I cannot
weaken the strength

1043
01:07:43,837 --> 01:07:45,586
of the regiment
in this emergency.

1044
01:07:45,654 --> 01:07:47,542
And I can't permit you
or any other officer

1045
01:07:47,607 --> 01:07:49,429
to risk their lives
for Mr. Stone.

1046
01:07:49,494 --> 01:07:51,599
But he's your son, and
we can save him, can't we?

1047
01:07:51,670 --> 01:07:53,231
That will be all,
Mr. McGregor.

1048
01:07:57,943 --> 01:07:59,404
Then take a look at that.

1049
01:07:59,479 --> 01:08:01,584
That's what Mohammed Khan
does to his prisoners.

1050
01:08:07,240 --> 01:08:09,570
That's quite unnecessary,
Mr. McGregor.

1051
01:08:09,891 --> 01:08:11,801
I know what may
happen to my son

1052
01:08:11,876 --> 01:08:13,916
through his own
disobedience and folly.

1053
01:08:15,331 --> 01:08:17,371
I'd just begun to think
I was wrong about you,

1054
01:08:17,444 --> 01:08:18,426
but I wasn't.

1055
01:08:18,500 --> 01:08:20,387
You haven't a human bone
in your body.

1056
01:08:20,451 --> 01:08:22,274
There's not a drop
of blood in your veins.

1057
01:08:22,340 --> 01:08:23,485
You're nothing but a-

1058
01:08:23,556 --> 01:08:24,668
McGregor.

1059
01:08:24,835 --> 01:08:26,461
So you'll sit here
with your regiment

1060
01:08:26,532 --> 01:08:28,092
while they kill
your son by inches.

1061
01:08:28,163 --> 01:08:29,143
Well, I won't!

1062
01:08:29,217 --> 01:08:31,245
I'm going after him whether
you like it or not.

1063
01:08:31,317 --> 01:08:32,555
Mr. McGregor!

1064
01:08:32,622 --> 01:08:35,112
Pending charges
of insubordination

1065
01:08:35,217 --> 01:08:37,551
you will please consider
yourself under arrest.

1066
01:08:37,617 --> 01:08:40,431
Mr. Forsythe, you will be
responsible for the prisoner.

1067
01:08:43,216 --> 01:08:44,645
You fooI.
Can't you see-

1068
01:08:44,720 --> 01:08:45,930
So you-
Mac!

1069
01:08:47,217 --> 01:08:48,394
Come along.

1070
01:08:52,720 --> 01:08:54,846
Well, I must say
you spoke your mind,

1071
01:08:54,915 --> 01:08:57,008
old colonial, if
there's any virtue in that.

1072
01:08:57,657 --> 01:08:59,516
"Regiment, duty,
you're improperly dressed. "

1073
01:08:59,582 --> 01:09:00,989
That's all
he cares about.

1074
01:09:01,054 --> 01:09:02,166
So they'll say,

1075
01:09:02,237 --> 01:09:04,277
"Very good, CoI. Stone,"
and pin another medal on him.

1076
01:09:04,350 --> 01:09:05,779
Or else he's...

1077
01:09:05,854 --> 01:09:07,479
Haven't you said enough,
McGregor?

1078
01:09:07,582 --> 01:09:09,240
The coloneI's right
and you know it.

1079
01:09:09,309 --> 01:09:11,197
You're only making it
harder for him.

1080
01:09:11,325 --> 01:09:13,813
If you take my advice,
you'll go over and apologize.

1081
01:09:13,886 --> 01:09:16,090
Not me. Apologize
after what he did?

1082
01:09:16,158 --> 01:09:18,287
Oh, for heaven's sake, man,
get some sense.

1083
01:09:18,770 --> 01:09:21,123
Do you suppose it was
an easy thing for him to do?

1084
01:09:21,189 --> 01:09:22,269
His own son?

1085
01:09:22,341 --> 01:09:23,394
Why wasn't it?

1086
01:09:23,658 --> 01:09:25,033
He doesn't care
about him.

1087
01:09:25,099 --> 01:09:26,593
He'd do the same thing
to any of us.

1088
01:09:26,666 --> 01:09:29,252
But to sit here and let them
pull his own son to pieces

1089
01:09:29,323 --> 01:09:30,849
because of a few
cases of ammunition-

1090
01:09:30,922 --> 01:09:32,580
Are you blind, man?

1091
01:09:32,811 --> 01:09:34,337
You think he doesn't care?

1092
01:09:34,539 --> 01:09:35,946
Well, I know he does.

1093
01:09:36,459 --> 01:09:38,019
Well, I suppose
if it were your son,

1094
01:09:38,090 --> 01:09:39,519
you'd sit here, too,
like a dummy.

1095
01:09:39,595 --> 01:09:40,577
You would not-

1096
01:09:40,651 --> 01:09:42,842
No, I should probably
have ordered the regiment out.

1097
01:09:42,910 --> 01:09:44,872
That's because I'm not
the man the colonel is.

1098
01:09:44,945 --> 01:09:45,927
Nor the soldier.

1099
01:09:46,001 --> 01:09:47,693
Well, if that's what
you call being a man

1100
01:09:47,763 --> 01:09:49,839
or a soldier, I don't
want any part of it.

1101
01:09:49,911 --> 01:09:51,024
Not me.

1102
01:09:51,096 --> 01:09:52,819
That kid needs him.
It's his own blood,

1103
01:09:52,887 --> 01:09:54,381
and if he cared
a hang about him-

1104
01:09:54,455 --> 01:09:56,910
Of course he cares. But
what's that got to do with it?

1105
01:09:57,560 --> 01:09:59,447
He loved his wife, too,
but he lost her.

1106
01:09:59,511 --> 01:10:00,493
She was American.

1107
01:10:00,567 --> 01:10:02,640
Couldn't stick the service,
couldn't understand.

1108
01:10:02,712 --> 01:10:05,521
So he chose the regiment then
just as he's doing now.

1109
01:10:05,586 --> 01:10:07,712
But that doesn't mean
he didn't care.

1110
01:10:08,035 --> 01:10:08,979
I know.

1111
01:10:09,118 --> 01:10:11,289
I ought to know.
We were Cubs together.

1112
01:10:11,550 --> 01:10:13,760
He put his whole souI
into the regiment,

1113
01:10:13,828 --> 01:10:15,170
and that's all he's had.

1114
01:10:15,685 --> 01:10:18,205
And he won't have that long,
either. Retirement.

1115
01:10:18,501 --> 01:10:20,388
He'll have an armchair
in the club,

1116
01:10:20,452 --> 01:10:22,459
and a window over the rag,
and that's all.

1117
01:10:22,532 --> 01:10:23,580
And he'll have nothing

1118
01:10:23,653 --> 01:10:25,758
if his boy doesn't carry on
in this regiment.

1119
01:10:26,212 --> 01:10:27,292
Then he'd have everything?

1120
01:10:27,364 --> 01:10:29,746
Of course he would.
That's what it means to him.

1121
01:10:29,822 --> 01:10:31,188
But you think
he'd let that make

1122
01:10:31,252 --> 01:10:32,999
any difference
to his orders, to his job?

1123
01:10:33,067 --> 01:10:34,594
Well, why shouldn't it?

1124
01:10:34,667 --> 01:10:36,489
Why can't he be
a little less of a soldier

1125
01:10:36,555 --> 01:10:37,604
and more of a man?

1126
01:10:37,677 --> 01:10:39,885
Why can't he forget
his blasted duty for once?

1127
01:10:39,954 --> 01:10:41,415
Man, you are blind!

1128
01:10:41,522 --> 01:10:42,798
Have you never thought

1129
01:10:42,865 --> 01:10:44,753
how for generation
after generation here,

1130
01:10:44,818 --> 01:10:46,476
a handfuI of men
have ordered the lives

1131
01:10:46,545 --> 01:10:48,454
of 300 million people?

1132
01:10:48,658 --> 01:10:50,927
It's because he's here,
and a few more like him.

1133
01:10:51,186 --> 01:10:53,514
Men of his breed
have made British India.

1134
01:10:53,707 --> 01:10:55,583
Men who put their jobs
above everything.

1135
01:10:55,647 --> 01:10:57,615
He wouldn't let death
move him from it

1136
01:10:57,688 --> 01:10:59,695
and he won't let love
move him from it.

1137
01:11:00,953 --> 01:11:04,025
When his breed of man
dies out, that's the end.

1138
01:11:05,215 --> 01:11:07,070
And it's
a better breed of man

1139
01:11:07,135 --> 01:11:08,891
than any of us will ever make.

1140
01:11:09,247 --> 01:11:10,588
Good night, gentlemen.

1141
01:11:13,054 --> 01:11:15,356
There's a great deaI
of speaking of minds

1142
01:11:15,423 --> 01:11:16,763
going on here tonight.

1143
01:11:17,719 --> 01:11:19,879
I didn't think
the old boy had it in him,

1144
01:11:20,138 --> 01:11:21,660
but he's right.

1145
01:11:22,822 --> 01:11:25,189
According to his way
of thinking, maybe.

1146
01:11:26,213 --> 01:11:27,873
It's funny,
your being out here

1147
01:11:27,944 --> 01:11:29,703
and thinking of it
in any other way.

1148
01:11:29,771 --> 01:11:31,429
On their side, huh?

1149
01:11:31,883 --> 01:11:34,305
Well, I'm not. So I'm
going to do something.

1150
01:11:34,540 --> 01:11:37,606
There's been enough thinking
and talking, too. I'm going.

1151
01:11:40,011 --> 01:11:41,759
Are you really, now?

1152
01:11:42,273 --> 01:11:45,325
You know, you put me
in a rather awkward position.

1153
01:11:45,394 --> 01:11:47,728
Look, I don't want
any trouble with you,

1154
01:11:47,794 --> 01:11:48,809
but I'm going.

1155
01:11:49,970 --> 01:11:51,825
Well, when do we start?

1156
01:11:53,335 --> 01:11:55,158
What do you mean "we"?

1157
01:11:55,480 --> 01:11:57,073
You're my prisoner, you know.

1158
01:11:57,209 --> 01:11:58,965
I couldn't let you
out of my sight.

1159
01:12:13,856 --> 01:12:15,710
I regret to have
to report, sir.

1160
01:12:15,776 --> 01:12:18,015
McGregor and Forsythe
have disappeared.

1161
01:12:18,147 --> 01:12:19,360
What, desertion?

1162
01:12:19,430 --> 01:12:21,666
I suppose it is,
technically.

1163
01:12:28,484 --> 01:12:30,708
Well, what did you expect?

1164
01:12:52,942 --> 01:12:56,057
" Sure I love
the dear silver "

1165
01:12:56,126 --> 01:12:58,260
" That shines in her hair "

1166
01:12:58,329 --> 01:13:00,435
" And the brow
that's all furrowed "

1167
01:13:00,506 --> 01:13:02,415
" and wrinkled with care "

1168
01:13:02,777 --> 01:13:07,087
" I kiss the dear fingers
so toiI-worn for me "

1169
01:13:07,449 --> 01:13:11,132
" Oh, God bless you
and keep you "

1170
01:13:11,584 --> 01:13:12,664
" Mother "

1171
01:13:13,375 --> 01:13:14,553
" Mcgregor "

1172
01:13:45,459 --> 01:13:48,306
Why do they want to talk
so many languages in India?

1173
01:13:48,724 --> 01:13:49,901
It's up to you.

1174
01:13:49,971 --> 01:13:51,564
You'll have to be
the talking merchant.

1175
01:13:51,891 --> 01:13:53,418
I'll be
the deaf and dumb one.

1176
01:14:18,625 --> 01:14:19,934
Well,
at least we're in.

1177
01:14:20,000 --> 01:14:21,593
I hope getting out
is as easy.

1178
01:14:27,558 --> 01:14:28,896
Trying to be funny?

1179
01:14:28,961 --> 01:14:30,383
No, I'm not
trying to be funny.

1180
01:14:30,457 --> 01:14:31,857
I'm scared stiff.

1181
01:14:32,112 --> 01:14:33,669
What are we
going to do now?

1182
01:14:33,741 --> 01:14:35,148
Try to look and act
like the rest

1183
01:14:35,213 --> 01:14:36,740
of these merchants.
Set up shops.

1184
01:14:36,813 --> 01:14:38,984
Sell a few doodads
while we take a look around.

1185
01:14:44,909 --> 01:14:47,331
I don't see anything
that looks like a plan.

1186
01:14:47,406 --> 01:14:48,425
As far as I can see,

1187
01:14:48,499 --> 01:14:50,604
we've just stuck our head
in the lion's mouth.

1188
01:14:50,675 --> 01:14:53,569
A very large and
unpleasant lion, too.

1189
01:14:54,152 --> 01:14:55,997
Suppose you
were Mohammed Khan,

1190
01:14:56,062 --> 01:14:57,335
where would you have put him?

1191
01:14:57,402 --> 01:14:59,736
Oh, no, you play first.
It'll be more fun.

1192
01:15:00,410 --> 01:15:01,458
All right.

1193
01:15:01,658 --> 01:15:03,480
You stay here
and unpack these things

1194
01:15:03,546 --> 01:15:04,757
and set up shop.

1195
01:15:04,826 --> 01:15:06,168
I'll take a look around.

1196
01:15:06,234 --> 01:15:08,535
Don't forget
you're deaf and dumb.

1197
01:16:48,430 --> 01:16:50,023
You'd better cut
your prices, Mac,

1198
01:16:50,094 --> 01:16:51,523
before I get my throat cut.

1199
01:16:51,949 --> 01:16:53,354
Do you think
she recognized us?

1200
01:16:53,419 --> 01:16:54,755
I hope not.

1201
01:16:55,075 --> 01:16:56,628
I don't think so.

1202
01:16:56,859 --> 01:16:58,419
Anyway,
we won't worry about it.

1203
01:16:58,491 --> 01:17:00,018
Did you see
anything interesting?

1204
01:17:00,091 --> 01:17:01,433
Not a thing.

1205
01:17:22,442 --> 01:17:23,904
What's that mean?
Time to go?

1206
01:17:23,978 --> 01:17:25,123
Yes.

1207
01:17:25,194 --> 01:17:27,496
But we're gonna stay
right here untiI we can-

1208
01:17:35,530 --> 01:17:37,668
He's in all right.
No doubt about that.

1209
01:17:37,738 --> 01:17:39,493
And doing rather well, too.

1210
01:17:39,561 --> 01:17:42,199
Clicquot.
I saw the labeI. Iced.

1211
01:17:42,460 --> 01:17:44,975
If that's the way Mohammed Khan
tortures his victims

1212
01:17:45,047 --> 01:17:47,414
I'd like to change places
with him for 10 minutes.

1213
01:17:47,479 --> 01:17:49,138
That guard's got
a key all right.

1214
01:17:49,207 --> 01:17:51,628
If we can last till night,
hit the guard over the head

1215
01:17:51,703 --> 01:17:53,590
get the kid out,
try and steal some horses-

1216
01:17:53,655 --> 01:17:54,865
Jump them over
a 40-foot wall

1217
01:17:54,935 --> 01:17:56,691
and then that mad dash
for the border.

1218
01:17:58,167 --> 01:17:59,890
Well, you think
of something better.

1219
01:18:12,996 --> 01:18:14,457
Mohammed Khan sent for us.

1220
01:18:14,532 --> 01:18:15,939
He wants to see
our rugs and laces.

1221
01:18:16,004 --> 01:18:17,793
Do you suppose?
No, I don't suppose.

1222
01:18:17,860 --> 01:18:19,900
Don't forget
you're deaf and dumb.

1223
01:18:37,585 --> 01:18:39,178
Oh, come, come, gentlemen.

1224
01:18:39,249 --> 01:18:41,071
It isn't everyday
that two British officers

1225
01:18:41,137 --> 01:18:44,072
prostrate themselves at the feet of
a poor border chieftain.

1226
01:18:44,145 --> 01:18:46,534
Mr. McGregor, Mr. Forsythe.

1227
01:18:47,601 --> 01:18:50,797
I told you, this Mardi Gras
would be a washout.

1228
01:18:50,960 --> 01:18:53,057
I had hoped the ColoneI
might come himself

1229
01:18:53,128 --> 01:18:55,005
but since he has so
very cleverly refused,

1230
01:18:55,132 --> 01:18:57,015
I welcome you
to my humble home.

1231
01:18:57,305 --> 01:18:58,968
You remember,
my dear, of course?

1232
01:18:59,038 --> 01:19:00,118
How could I forget?

1233
01:19:00,190 --> 01:19:01,913
They were such
charming dinner companions.

1234
01:19:01,982 --> 01:19:03,673
Dinner. Yes, of course.

1235
01:19:03,742 --> 01:19:05,433
You will dine with me
surely, gentlemen,

1236
01:19:05,502 --> 01:19:07,225
to try my poor savage fare?

1237
01:19:07,294 --> 01:19:10,458
I know you must be anxious
to meet my guest of honor.

1238
01:19:11,614 --> 01:19:14,264
I wouldn't do that
if I were you, Mr. McGregor.

1239
01:19:26,347 --> 01:19:28,965
Yes, I've-I've seen
good cricket in my time.

1240
01:19:29,035 --> 01:19:30,595
I was an Oxford man,
you know.

1241
01:19:30,667 --> 01:19:32,423
But I must compliment you,
Mr. Forsythe,

1242
01:19:32,491 --> 01:19:33,636
on your delivery.

1243
01:19:33,707 --> 01:19:34,635
Superb.

1244
01:19:34,699 --> 01:19:35,877
Oh, charming
compliment.

1245
01:19:36,042 --> 01:19:38,530
My only regret is that
it wasn't a hand grenade.

1246
01:19:38,603 --> 01:19:39,810
A charming thought.

1247
01:19:39,879 --> 01:19:41,019
A charming dinner.

1248
01:19:41,089 --> 01:19:43,347
The mutton
was, uh, excellent.

1249
01:19:43,414 --> 01:19:44,839
Always mutton.

1250
01:19:45,074 --> 01:19:47,597
We have mutton or chicken
up here. But, as you say,

1251
01:19:47,669 --> 01:19:50,672
good mutton, quite the equaI
of your English South Down.

1252
01:19:50,744 --> 01:19:53,111
Now you put me in a very
difficult position.

1253
01:19:53,176 --> 01:19:55,696
Pride of country urges me
to argue the point.

1254
01:19:55,864 --> 01:19:57,839
But my position
as, uh...

1255
01:19:57,912 --> 01:19:59,319
as a guest,
shall we say-

1256
01:19:59,384 --> 01:20:02,286
By all means a guest,
for the time being.

1257
01:20:02,456 --> 01:20:04,109
For the time being, huh?

1258
01:20:04,656 --> 01:20:06,274
Pass the wine.

1259
01:20:06,344 --> 01:20:07,798
My position
as a guest

1260
01:20:07,872 --> 01:20:09,115
for the time being,
of course,

1261
01:20:09,183 --> 01:20:10,939
inclines me
to agree with you.

1262
01:20:11,455 --> 01:20:12,801
Well, a compliment indeed,

1263
01:20:12,867 --> 01:20:15,357
that we can approach the excellence
of anything British.

1264
01:20:16,005 --> 01:20:18,242
I'm fed up with this
cat-and-mouse business.

1265
01:20:18,309 --> 01:20:19,356
Let's talk sense.

1266
01:20:19,429 --> 01:20:21,982
You've got us here and now what
are you going to do with us?

1267
01:20:22,053 --> 01:20:23,482
Mac, manners,
manners.

1268
01:20:23,781 --> 01:20:26,050
By the way, we didn't
thank the Khan sahib

1269
01:20:26,117 --> 01:20:28,412
for our charming
and picturesque raiment.

1270
01:20:28,637 --> 01:20:30,732
Suppose we stay
with the subject?

1271
01:20:30,834 --> 01:20:32,289
I'm quite prepared
to supply you

1272
01:20:32,364 --> 01:20:34,153
with horses to return
to your regiment.

1273
01:20:34,572 --> 01:20:36,677
You can tell your coloneI
that some of my men

1274
01:20:36,748 --> 01:20:38,893
misunderstood his son's
innocent flirtation.

1275
01:20:38,962 --> 01:20:40,423
Of course,
when I found it out,

1276
01:20:40,498 --> 01:20:41,807
I punished them at once.

1277
01:20:41,873 --> 01:20:44,426
An easy explanation of how
I came to set you free.

1278
01:20:44,497 --> 01:20:45,839
And, uh,
what's the catch?

1279
01:20:45,906 --> 01:20:48,972
You have only to answer
two very simple questions:

1280
01:20:49,842 --> 01:20:52,704
By what route is
the ammunition train coming

1281
01:20:53,319 --> 01:20:55,165
and just where does
the regiment plan

1282
01:20:55,229 --> 01:20:56,632
to meet it for convoy?

1283
01:20:57,977 --> 01:20:59,864
Well, when the furry
little animaI

1284
01:20:59,929 --> 01:21:02,649
jumped out of the bag
he really jumped, didn't he?

1285
01:21:04,351 --> 01:21:05,780
Well, gentlemen.

1286
01:21:07,871 --> 01:21:10,043
We have ways
to make men talk.

1287
01:21:12,095 --> 01:21:14,266
If you'll forgive me,
I- I have a headache.

1288
01:21:14,335 --> 01:21:16,184
Oh, I'm sorry, my dear.

1289
01:21:18,892 --> 01:21:20,795
Madame Volkanskaya
finds our methods

1290
01:21:20,870 --> 01:21:22,332
in this part of the world

1291
01:21:22,405 --> 01:21:24,260
a little too direct
for her taste.

1292
01:21:24,325 --> 01:21:26,114
Your brandy, gentlemen.

1293
01:21:33,196 --> 01:21:35,585
Take it. We may need it.

1294
01:21:42,937 --> 01:21:44,175
I regret this,

1295
01:21:44,243 --> 01:21:46,731
but thanks to your coloneI's
cold heart and cold brain

1296
01:21:46,803 --> 01:21:48,843
I have no other choice,
and very little time.

1297
01:21:48,914 --> 01:21:50,605
Now that we're
no longer guests,

1298
01:21:50,674 --> 01:21:52,586
tell him what you
really think of the mutton.

1299
01:21:52,662 --> 01:21:53,777
Oh, yes.

1300
01:21:55,673 --> 01:21:57,812
As much as I regret
to say this,

1301
01:21:57,881 --> 01:21:59,669
your mutton
is undoubtedly-

1302
01:21:59,736 --> 01:22:01,046
"Rotten" is the word.

1303
01:22:01,113 --> 01:22:02,225
Thanks, Mac.

1304
01:22:29,848 --> 01:22:32,139
Come, now, gentlemen,
must I proceed

1305
01:22:32,205 --> 01:22:34,725
to these absurd
and unpleasant extremes?

1306
01:22:37,421 --> 01:22:39,243
Little bamboo slivers

1307
01:22:39,821 --> 01:22:42,025
but when they're driven
under the fingernails

1308
01:22:42,478 --> 01:22:43,726
and lighted,

1309
01:22:44,210 --> 01:22:46,283
we find them
very effective.

1310
01:22:46,386 --> 01:22:48,558
Bring the other two gentlemen
a little bit closer

1311
01:22:48,627 --> 01:22:50,088
so they can see well.

1312
01:22:57,017 --> 01:23:00,246
I shall proceed first
with Mr. McGregor.

1313
01:24:45,646 --> 01:24:47,502
I'll get you some water.

1314
01:24:47,599 --> 01:24:49,392
I'd rather have
a cigarette, Mac.

1315
01:25:26,376 --> 01:25:29,692
Dentist once in MontreaI
hit a nerve.

1316
01:25:30,216 --> 01:25:32,004
It hurt almost as bad.

1317
01:25:32,904 --> 01:25:35,271
Well, he's been
to a dentist.

1318
01:25:51,221 --> 01:25:52,595
Let me alone!

1319
01:26:10,241 --> 01:26:11,932
Come on, Tania.
Don't faiI me, Tania.

1320
01:26:12,001 --> 01:26:13,659
Come along,
Mohammed Khan.

1321
01:26:14,242 --> 01:26:15,190
Show some speed!

1322
01:26:15,329 --> 01:26:16,442
Tania!

1323
01:26:16,514 --> 01:26:18,270
For dear
old Forsythe.

1324
01:26:18,338 --> 01:26:20,509
Tania! Tania!
Run, jump, do something!

1325
01:26:20,578 --> 01:26:21,658
Do anything.

1326
01:26:21,730 --> 01:26:23,006
That's right.
Here we go.

1327
01:26:23,073 --> 01:26:24,382
Tania!
One jump.

1328
01:26:24,481 --> 01:26:26,749
Come on, Mohammed Khan,
take that hurdle.

1329
01:26:26,815 --> 01:26:29,177
Ah, Mohammed Khan,
by half a length.

1330
01:26:29,402 --> 01:26:32,806
That makes 40 million
Rupees you owe me.

1331
01:26:33,583 --> 01:26:35,525
Another day of this,
and I'm broke.

1332
01:26:35,599 --> 01:26:37,737
Another day of this, we'll
be going around in circles

1333
01:26:37,806 --> 01:26:39,181
like
those cockroaches.

1334
01:26:39,822 --> 01:26:41,961
Ah, I wonder when these
whiskers stop itching

1335
01:26:42,031 --> 01:26:43,405
and begin to be a beard!

1336
01:26:43,822 --> 01:26:45,732
Foulest torture
ever invented.

1337
01:26:45,838 --> 01:26:47,594
Keep us in a cell
that crawls

1338
01:26:47,662 --> 01:26:49,604
and fix us so
we can't scratch.

1339
01:27:11,755 --> 01:27:14,535
All the Khan's horses
and all the Khan's men.

1340
01:27:19,929 --> 01:27:21,554
It didn't
take him long.

1341
01:27:21,913 --> 01:27:23,320
I'd like to
have seen the look

1342
01:27:23,384 --> 01:27:24,628
on the ColoneI's face.

1343
01:27:42,471 --> 01:27:44,891
It looks as if they were
expecting trouble.

1344
01:27:56,965 --> 01:27:58,459
There's only one answer.

1345
01:27:58,597 --> 01:28:00,124
The ColoneI's
after them.

1346
01:28:00,421 --> 01:28:01,948
And with all
the ammunition here,

1347
01:28:02,020 --> 01:28:03,899
there's nothing to
keep him in GopaI.

1348
01:28:03,965 --> 01:28:05,299
With those machine guns

1349
01:28:05,366 --> 01:28:06,822
and two million rounds
of ammunition

1350
01:28:06,895 --> 01:28:08,425
the regiment
wouldn't have a chance.

1351
01:28:08,499 --> 01:28:10,157
The old Ramrod's a fooI
to try it.

1352
01:28:10,227 --> 01:28:11,471
He will, though.

1353
01:28:11,539 --> 01:28:13,262
There's nothing much
we can do about it.

1354
01:28:19,219 --> 01:28:21,390
I wish I had
my toodle-oodle here.

1355
01:28:21,587 --> 01:28:23,790
I'd play you some
wild Scotch airs.

1356
01:28:23,859 --> 01:28:25,768
Over my dead body,
you would.

1357
01:28:25,843 --> 01:28:27,330
You know, that's
rather clever, Mac.

1358
01:28:27,403 --> 01:28:29,781
Why don't you say it?
Why don't you say what you're thinking?

1359
01:28:29,857 --> 01:28:30,801
Forget it!

1360
01:28:30,875 --> 01:28:33,115
I'm to blame. I told them,
that's what you're thinking.

1361
01:28:33,183 --> 01:28:34,361
Why don't you say it?
Shut up!

1362
01:28:34,431 --> 01:28:37,213
All right, I told them
and why shouldn't I? For him?

1363
01:28:37,536 --> 01:28:38,877
To stand there and watch

1364
01:28:38,943 --> 01:28:41,278
and know all the time
I was gonna be next

1365
01:28:41,343 --> 01:28:44,212
to have your nails torn off
and those pincers

1366
01:28:44,287 --> 01:28:46,229
and burning sticks
driven into you untiI...

1367
01:28:46,303 --> 01:28:48,125
And things you
can't even talk about.

1368
01:28:54,856 --> 01:28:56,512
Why should I stand all that?

1369
01:28:56,582 --> 01:28:58,498
For what? For him?

1370
01:28:58,797 --> 01:29:02,244
For a service that makes him
like he's been to me?

1371
01:29:03,916 --> 01:29:05,574
He left me here, didn't he?

1372
01:29:05,644 --> 01:29:06,953
He knew what they'd do.

1373
01:29:07,021 --> 01:29:08,908
He wouldn't come
after me, not him.

1374
01:29:08,972 --> 01:29:10,947
Regiment, service, duty!

1375
01:29:11,212 --> 01:29:13,187
Why should I stand
what you did for them?

1376
01:29:13,260 --> 01:29:14,946
Why should I?
Why should any of us? Why?

1377
01:29:18,232 --> 01:29:19,950
I told you to forget it.

1378
01:29:20,403 --> 01:29:21,931
All right, Mac.

1379
01:29:22,037 --> 01:29:23,863
But I still
don't understand why.

1380
01:29:23,930 --> 01:29:25,937
Why? Well...

1381
01:29:26,169 --> 01:29:28,558
Well, there are some things
they don't teach you

1382
01:29:28,634 --> 01:29:30,543
in military college.
Can't, I guess.

1383
01:29:30,745 --> 01:29:34,128
India's big, you know.
There are 300 million people

1384
01:29:34,265 --> 01:29:36,469
and run by, uh,
just a handfuI of men.

1385
01:29:36,537 --> 01:29:38,769
The-The-The job comes first.

1386
01:29:39,346 --> 01:29:40,388
Like old Ramrod,

1387
01:29:40,461 --> 01:29:42,524
you can't let death
move you, nor love.

1388
01:29:42,595 --> 01:29:43,640
And it's like...

1389
01:29:43,713 --> 01:29:45,273
How can I tell you
what it's all about

1390
01:29:45,344 --> 01:29:46,806
when I don't know
myself?

1391
01:29:56,422 --> 01:29:58,811
"'The time has
come,'the Walrus said,

1392
01:29:58,887 --> 01:30:00,294
"'To speak of many things

1393
01:30:00,358 --> 01:30:02,395
"'Of ships and shoes
and sealing-wax,

1394
01:30:02,467 --> 01:30:03,835
Of cabbages and kings. "'

1395
01:30:03,900 --> 01:30:05,268
Oh, shut up!

1396
01:30:05,907 --> 01:30:07,657
You don't like
poetry?

1397
01:30:07,885 --> 01:30:09,740
How should I know?
I never read any.

1398
01:30:11,117 --> 01:30:13,262
Perhaps something
more rugged.

1399
01:30:14,995 --> 01:30:17,450
"Ever the faith endures,

1400
01:30:17,779 --> 01:30:19,502
"England, my England

1401
01:30:20,723 --> 01:30:23,276
"Take and break us,
we are yours

1402
01:30:23,347 --> 01:30:25,005
"England, my own

1403
01:30:26,893 --> 01:30:30,196
"Life is good, joy runs high

1404
01:30:30,398 --> 01:30:33,045
"Between English earth and sky

1405
01:30:33,338 --> 01:30:36,240
"Death is death
and we shall die

1406
01:30:36,442 --> 01:30:39,677
"to the Song
on your bugles blown, England

1407
01:30:40,672 --> 01:30:43,193
To the stars on
your bugles blown!"

1408
01:30:45,184 --> 01:30:47,039
If I had known I was
going to say all this,

1409
01:30:47,104 --> 01:30:48,533
I would have
brought my violin.

1410
01:31:21,012 --> 01:31:23,662
You weren't by any chance thinking
how nice it would be

1411
01:31:23,732 --> 01:31:26,602
if someone spilled the fire
into that ammunition, were you?

1412
01:31:29,178 --> 01:31:31,251
About 200 yards,
I'd say.

1413
01:31:31,418 --> 01:31:32,793
Nearer a 100.

1414
01:31:33,082 --> 01:31:35,384
My last year in Oxford
I won the 220.

1415
01:31:35,738 --> 01:31:37,842
I ran the 100
in 10 flat at McGill.

1416
01:31:38,103 --> 01:31:41,090
It's nearer 200.
And where's McGill?

1417
01:31:42,182 --> 01:31:43,639
Mcgill's in MontreaI.

1418
01:31:43,713 --> 01:31:45,404
And this is a job
for a 100-yard man.

1419
01:31:45,889 --> 01:31:47,580
Forget I'm your
superior officer?

1420
01:31:47,649 --> 01:31:49,438
Forget you're
my prisoner?

1421
01:31:50,785 --> 01:31:51,931
Toss you?

1422
01:31:59,175 --> 01:32:00,801
The cockroaches.

1423
01:32:00,871 --> 01:32:02,872
If Tania gets to
the wall first, I win.

1424
01:32:03,040 --> 01:32:05,332
It's a go?
Mohammed Khan! Come on!

1425
01:32:05,398 --> 01:32:06,918
Tania, what's the matter?

1426
01:32:06,991 --> 01:32:09,707
Mohammed Khan again!
It's my job.

1427
01:32:10,862 --> 01:32:13,066
Your luck's as good
as ever, Mac.

1428
01:32:13,871 --> 01:32:15,277
And now all I have to do

1429
01:32:15,342 --> 01:32:17,067
is figure a way
to get out of here.

1430
01:32:17,136 --> 01:32:18,220
That's all.

1431
01:32:26,543 --> 01:32:27,782
Too late, sir.

1432
01:32:27,849 --> 01:32:29,305
Hopeless to
attack that strength.

1433
01:32:29,379 --> 01:32:31,378
If we retire now
and that ammunition

1434
01:32:31,451 --> 01:32:33,393
is distributed
amongst the tribes...

1435
01:32:33,467 --> 01:32:34,743
You know what that means.

1436
01:32:34,811 --> 01:32:36,153
Yes, a costly job,
sir.

1437
01:32:36,219 --> 01:32:37,299
I know.

1438
01:32:37,435 --> 01:32:39,323
But it's worth
the whole regiment.

1439
01:32:39,579 --> 01:32:41,881
Squadron, wheel into line.
Gallop!

1440
01:32:49,217 --> 01:32:50,869
What are you doing?

1441
01:32:51,480 --> 01:32:53,197
I'm trying to wear
a hole in the wall

1442
01:32:53,264 --> 01:32:54,719
so we can all
climb through.

1443
01:33:00,808 --> 01:33:02,052
It occurred to me,
gentlemen

1444
01:33:02,120 --> 01:33:04,422
that you might like to know
what is to become of you.

1445
01:33:04,488 --> 01:33:07,009
I'm expecting a visit from
your colonel in a few minutes.

1446
01:33:07,082 --> 01:33:09,475
I can assure you he will
receive a very warm reception.

1447
01:33:09,550 --> 01:33:11,787
In the coming engagement,
if the Colonel escapes

1448
01:33:11,854 --> 01:33:13,739
I shall send you all
back to him alive.

1449
01:33:13,804 --> 01:33:16,096
If he is captured,
you will all die.

1450
01:33:16,512 --> 01:33:18,359
In any case,
I shall have the pleasure

1451
01:33:18,424 --> 01:33:20,461
of bringing the ColoneI
face to face with a son

1452
01:33:20,533 --> 01:33:22,256
who betrayed his Empire.

1453
01:33:35,899 --> 01:33:37,556
Very foolish,
Mr. Forsythe.

1454
01:33:37,626 --> 01:33:40,298
You should always temper
courage with judgment.

1455
01:33:51,842 --> 01:33:53,402
That's a fooI thing
to do.

1456
01:33:53,474 --> 01:33:54,849
We'll get it
soon enough.

1457
01:34:03,104 --> 01:34:04,755
Did you get a gun, too?

1458
01:34:05,175 --> 01:34:07,556
Just about enough powder
in those, I think,

1459
01:34:08,239 --> 01:34:09,668
to blow that lock off.

1460
01:34:10,095 --> 01:34:12,037
It took us five days
to think of that.

1461
01:34:12,111 --> 01:34:13,257
Us?

1462
01:34:15,343 --> 01:34:17,383
Take a little water and mix
enough straw and mud

1463
01:34:17,455 --> 01:34:18,917
to seal this lock.

1464
01:34:25,141 --> 01:34:26,890
What do we use
for a fuse?

1465
01:34:39,612 --> 01:34:40,725
Mac.

1466
01:34:40,796 --> 01:34:41,810
Yeah.

1467
01:34:41,884 --> 01:34:43,859
This idea, I'm in on it.

1468
01:34:43,932 --> 01:34:45,492
It was my fault, all this,

1469
01:34:45,564 --> 01:34:47,258
and if there's any way...
I mean-

1470
01:34:47,327 --> 01:34:49,336
Sure, I know.
Ready with that wick?

1471
01:34:49,632 --> 01:34:51,447
I mean, there's not
much left that...

1472
01:34:51,512 --> 01:34:53,163
Well, I couldn't go back,
like he said,

1473
01:34:53,233 --> 01:34:54,981
not to the regiment
or to England.

1474
01:34:56,425 --> 01:34:58,149
If anybody's going
to take any chances,

1475
01:34:58,217 --> 01:34:59,329
I'll take them.

1476
01:34:59,401 --> 01:35:00,611
Sure you're in on it.

1477
01:35:00,680 --> 01:35:02,306
Never thought of it
any other way.

1478
01:35:02,377 --> 01:35:04,003
Just stick close and
do what you're told

1479
01:35:04,073 --> 01:35:05,316
till we get this open.

1480
01:35:21,494 --> 01:35:23,599
There's someone on that tower
with a machine gun.

1481
01:35:23,670 --> 01:35:25,874
Let me get it and cover you
while you make a run for it.

1482
01:35:25,942 --> 01:35:26,890
All right.

1483
01:35:28,470 --> 01:35:29,931
Look, I've got a hunch

1484
01:35:30,006 --> 01:35:31,348
we're going to
get out of this.

1485
01:35:31,414 --> 01:35:33,934
We can't let the old man or
anybody know what's happened.

1486
01:36:54,730 --> 01:36:56,704
Mohammed Khan!
Mohammed Khan!

1487
01:37:10,410 --> 01:37:11,457
This way.

1488
01:37:25,430 --> 01:37:27,089
All right, Mac,
you keep me covered.

1489
01:37:27,159 --> 01:37:28,752
I can make it from here.

1490
01:37:55,812 --> 01:37:58,463
Bugles. Trumpets.

1491
01:37:59,524 --> 01:38:01,181
Man needs seasoning.

1492
01:38:08,336 --> 01:38:09,514
Poetry!

1493
01:39:35,352 --> 01:39:38,443
Mac! Mac, I... I...

1494
01:39:39,723 --> 01:39:42,080
He did it for me.
To undo what I did!

1495
01:39:50,180 --> 01:39:52,003
The last thing
Mac asked you...

1496
01:39:52,645 --> 01:39:54,652
the old man mustn't know.

1497
01:39:54,853 --> 01:39:58,049
It's just as good a way
of paying what you owe.

1498
01:41:06,123 --> 01:41:08,098
Mother McGregor.

1499
01:41:30,552 --> 01:41:32,276
Lt. John Forsythe

1500
01:41:32,568 --> 01:41:34,805
by command of His Majesty
the King-Emperor,

1501
01:41:34,936 --> 01:41:36,398
I confer upon you

1502
01:41:36,472 --> 01:41:38,602
the distinguished
service order.

1503
01:41:45,119 --> 01:41:49,145
Second Lt. Donald Stone,
41st Bengal Lancers.

1504
01:41:49,664 --> 01:41:52,964
For conspicuous gallantry
and devotion to duty.

1505
01:41:53,542 --> 01:41:56,324
He attacked single-handed,
a group of the enemy

1506
01:41:56,390 --> 01:41:58,113
and killed their leader

1507
01:41:58,181 --> 01:42:00,602
thus demoralizing
hostile forces

1508
01:42:00,677 --> 01:42:02,774
at a moment when
the success of our arms

1509
01:42:02,844 --> 01:42:05,202
at Mogala was in the balance.

1510
01:42:10,861 --> 01:42:12,748
Second Lt. Donald Stone

1511
01:42:13,164 --> 01:42:15,466
by Command of His Majesty
the King-Emperor

1512
01:42:15,532 --> 01:42:18,386
I confer upon you the
distinguished service order.

1513
01:42:36,537 --> 01:42:38,425
Lt. Alan McGregor

1514
01:42:38,553 --> 01:42:41,204
41st Bengal Lancers,
deceased.

1515
01:42:41,819 --> 01:42:43,166
For valor.

1516
01:42:43,424 --> 01:42:45,431
At the sacrifice of his life

1517
01:42:45,504 --> 01:42:47,925
he destroyed enemy
